	<H1 CLASS="start2">
Sextus&#8203;<A CLASS="ref" ID="ref1" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Frontinus/De_Aquis/text*.html#note1
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,EdNote,WIDTH,180)"
onMouseOut="nd();">1</A> Julius Frontinus:
	<BR><SPAN CLASS="green">
The Aqueducts of Rome
	</SPAN></H1>

	<H2 CLASS="start emend" ID="p331"><SPAN CLASS="pagenum"> p331 </SPAN>
[Preface]
	</H2>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A HREF="
L/Roman/Texts/Frontinus/De_Aquis/text*.html#1.1
	"TARGET="Frontinus"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,LatinOriginal,WIDTH,180)"
onMouseOut="nd();"><IMG TITLE="" WIDTH="30" HEIGHT="20" SRC="
Images/Utility/Flags/medium/Vatican.gif
	" ALT="[Legamen ad versionem Latinam]"></A>
	<A CLASS="chapter" NAME="1.1">1</A>
Inasmuch as every task assigned by the Emperor demands especial attention; and inasmuch as I am incited, not merely to diligence, but also to devotion, when any matter is entrusted to me, be it as a consequence of my natural sense of responsibility or of my fidelity; and inasmuch as Nerva Augustus (an emperor of whom I am at a loss to say whether he devotes more industry or love to the State) has laid upon me the duties of water commissioner, an office which concerns not merely the convenience but also the health and even the safety of the City, and which has always been administered by the most eminent men of our State; now therefore I deem it of the first and greatest importance to familiarize myself with the business I have undertaken, a policy which I have always made a principle in other affairs.

	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A HREF="
L/Roman/Texts/Frontinus/De_Aquis/text*.html#1.2
	"TARGET="Frontinus"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,LatinOriginal,WIDTH,180)"
onMouseOut="nd();"><IMG TITLE="" WIDTH="30" HEIGHT="20" SRC="
Images/Utility/Flags/medium/Vatican.gif
	" ALT="[Legamen ad versionem Latinam]"></A>
	<A CLASS="chapter" NAME="1.2">2</A>
For I believe that there is no surer foundation for any business than this, and that it would be otherwise impossible to determine what ought to be done, what ought to be avoided; likewise that there is nothing so disgraceful for a decent man as to conduct an office delegated to him, according to the instructions


<A ID="p333"><SPAN CLASS="pagenum"> p333 </SPAN></A>of assistants. Yet precisely this is inevitable whenever a person inexperienced in the matter in hand has to have recourse to the practical knowledge of subordinates. For though the latter play a necessary rôle in the way of rendering assistance, yet they are, as it were, but the hands and tools of the directing head. Observing, therefore, the practice which I have followed in many offices, I have gathered in this sketch (into one systematic body, so to speak) such facts, hitherto scattered, as I have been able to get together, which bear on the general subject, and which might serve to guide me in my administration. Now in the case of other books which I have written after practical experience, I consulted the interests of my predecessors. The present treatise also may be found useful by my own successor, but it will serve especially for my own instruction and guidance, being prepared, as it is, at the beginning of my administration.

	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A HREF="
L/Roman/Texts/Frontinus/De_Aquis/text*.html#1.3
	"TARGET="Frontinus"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,LatinOriginal,WIDTH,180)"
onMouseOut="nd();"><IMG TITLE="" WIDTH="30" HEIGHT="20" SRC="
Images/Utility/Flags/medium/Vatican.gif
	" ALT="[Legamen ad versionem Latinam]"></A>
	<A CLASS="chapter" NAME="1.3">3</A>
And lest I seem to have omitted anything requisite to a familiarity with the entire subject, I will first set down the names of the waters which enter the City of Rome; then I will tell by whom, under what consuls, and in what year after the founding of the City each one was brought in; then at what point and at what milestone each water was taken; how far each is carried in a subterranean channel, how far on substructures,&#8203;<A CLASS="ref" ID="ref2" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Frontinus/De_Aquis/text*.html#note2
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,EdNote,WIDTH,180)"
onMouseOut="nd();">2</A> how far on arches. Then I will give the elevation&#8203;<A CLASS="ref" ID="ref3" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Frontinus/De_Aquis/text*.html#note3
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,EdNote,WIDTH,180)"
onMouseOut="nd();">3</A> of each, [the plan] of the taps, and the distributions that are made from them;


<A ID="p335"><SPAN CLASS="pagenum"> p335 </SPAN></A>how much each aqueduct brings to points outside the City, what proportion to each quarter within the City; how many public reservoirs there are, and from these how much is delivered to public works, how much to ornamental fountains&#8203;<A CLASS="ref" ID="ref4" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Frontinus/De_Aquis/text*.html#note4
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,EdNote,WIDTH,180)"
onMouseOut="nd();">4</A> (<SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">munera</SPAN>, as the more polite call them), how much to the water-basins; how much is granted in the name of Caesar; how much for private uses by the favour of the Emperor; what is the law with regard to the construction and maintenance of the aqueducts, what penalties enforce it, whether established by resolutions of the Senate or by edicts of the Emperors.

<!-- p337 is blank -->
	<H2 CLASS="start" ID="p339"><SPAN CLASS="pagenum"> p339 </SPAN>
Book I
	</H2>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A HREF="
L/Roman/Texts/Frontinus/De_Aquis/text*.html#1.4
	"TARGET="Frontinus"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,LatinOriginal,WIDTH,180)"
onMouseOut="nd();"><IMG TITLE="" WIDTH="30" HEIGHT="20" SRC="
Images/Utility/Flags/medium/Vatican.gif
	" ALT="[Legamen ad versionem Latinam]"></A>
	<A CLASS="chapter" NAME="1.4">4</A>
For four hundred and <SPAN CLASS="whole">forty-one</SPAN> years from the foundation of the City, the Romans were satisfied with the use of such waters as they drew from the Tiber, from wells, or from springs. Esteem for springs still continues, and is observed with veneration. They are believed to bring healing to the sick, as, for example, the springs of the Camenae,&#8203;<A CLASS="ref" ID="ref5a" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Frontinus/De_Aquis/text*.html#note5
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,EdNote,WIDTH,180)"
onMouseOut="nd();">5a</A> of Apollo,&#8203;<A CLASS="ref" ID="ref5b" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Frontinus/De_Aquis/text*.html#note5
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,EdNote,WIDTH,180)"
onMouseOut="nd();">5b</A> and of Juturna.&#8203;<A CLASS="ref" ID="ref6" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Frontinus/De_Aquis/text*.html#note6
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,EdNote,WIDTH,180)"
onMouseOut="nd();">6</A> But there now run into the City: the Appian aqueduct, Old Anio, Marcia, Tepula, Julia, Virgo, Alsietina, which is also called Augusta, Claudia, New Anio.


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A HREF="
L/Roman/Texts/Frontinus/De_Aquis/text*.html#1.5
	"TARGET="Frontinus"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,LatinOriginal,WIDTH,180)"
onMouseOut="nd();"><IMG TITLE="" WIDTH="30" HEIGHT="20" SRC="
Images/Utility/Flags/medium/Vatican.gif
	" ALT="[Legamen ad versionem Latinam]"></A>
	<A CLASS="chapter" NAME="1.5">5</A>
In the <SPAN CLASS="whole">consul</SPAN>&shy;ship of Marcus Valerius Maximus and Publius Decius Mus,&#8203;<A CLASS="ref" ID="ref7" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Frontinus/De_Aquis/text*.html#note7
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,EdNote,WIDTH,180)"
onMouseOut="nd();">7</A> in the thirtieth year after the beginning of the Samnite War, the Appian aqueduct was brought into the City by Appius Claudius Crassus, the Censor, who afterwards received the surname of "the Blind," the same man who had charge of constructing the Appian Way from the Porta Capena&#8203;<A CLASS="ref" ID="ref8" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Frontinus/De_Aquis/text*.html#note8
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,EdNote,WIDTH,180)"
onMouseOut="nd();">8</A> as far as the City of Capua. As colleague in the <SPAN CLASS="whole">censor</SPAN>&shy;ship Appius had Gaius Plautius, to whom was given the name of "the Hunter"&#8203;<A CLASS="ref" ID="ref9" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Frontinus/De_Aquis/text*.html#note9
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,EdNote,WIDTH,180)"
onMouseOut="nd();">9</A> for having discovered the springs of this water. But since Plautius resigned the <SPAN CLASS="whole">censor</SPAN>&shy;ship within a year and six months,&#8203;<A CLASS="ref" ID="ref10" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Frontinus/De_Aquis/text*.html#note10
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,EdNote,WIDTH,180)"
onMouseOut="nd();">10</A> under the mistaken impression that


<A ID="p341"><SPAN CLASS="pagenum"> p341 </SPAN></A>his colleague would do the same, the honour of giving his name to the aqueduct fell to Appius alone, who, by various subterfuges, is reported to have extended the term of his <SPAN CLASS="whole">censor</SPAN>&shy;ship, until he should complete both the Way and this aqueduct. The intake of the Appia is on the Lucullan estate, between the seventh and eighth milestones, on the Praenestine Way, on a cross-road, <A CLASS="conversion"
onMouseOver="return Ebox('1.15 km',WIDTH,84)"
onMouseOut="nd();">•</A>780 paces&#8203;<A CLASS="ref" ID="ref11" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Frontinus/De_Aquis/text*.html#note11
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,EdNote,WIDTH,180)"
onMouseOut="nd();">11</A> to the left.&#8203;<A CLASS="ref" ID="ref12" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Frontinus/De_Aquis/text*.html#note12
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,EdNote,WIDTH,180)"
onMouseOut="nd();">12</A> From its intake to the Salinae at the Porta Trigemina,&#8203;<A CLASS="ref" ID="ref13" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Frontinus/De_Aquis/text*.html#note13
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,EdNote,WIDTH,180)"
onMouseOut="nd();">13</A> its channel has a length of <A CLASS="conversion"
onMouseOver="return Ebox('16.56 km',WIDTH,96)"
onMouseOut="nd();">•</A>11,190 paces, of which <A CLASS="conversion"
onMouseOver="return Ebox('16.47 km',WIDTH,96)"
onMouseOut="nd();">•</A>11,130 paces run <SPAN CLASS="whole">under</SPAN>&shy;ground, while above ground <A CLASS="conversion"
onMouseOver="return Ebox('90 m',WIDTH,50)"
onMouseOut="nd();">•</A>sixty paces are carried on substructures and, near the Porta Capena, on arches. Near Spes Vetus,&#8203;<A CLASS="ref" ID="ref14" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Frontinus/De_Aquis/text*.html#note14
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,EdNote,WIDTH,180)"
onMouseOut="nd();">14</A> on the edge of the Torquatian and Epaphroditian Gardens, there joins it a branch of Augusta, added by Augustus as a supplementary supply
	<SPAN CLASS="crux">*
	<IMG TITLE="" WIDTH="49" HEIGHT="12" SRC="
Images/Utility/empty.gif
	" ALT="lacuna"></SPAN>
This branch has its intake at the sixth milestone, on the Praenestine Way, on a cross-road, <A CLASS="conversion"
onMouseOver="return Ebox('1.45 km',WIDTH,84)"
onMouseOut="nd();">•</A>980 paces to the left, near the Collatian Way. Its course, by <SPAN CLASS="whole">under</SPAN>&shy;ground channel, extends to <A CLASS="conversion"
onMouseOver="return Ebox('9.4 km',WIDTH,72)"
onMouseOut="nd();">•</A>6,380 paces before reaching The Twins.&#8203;<A CLASS="ref" ID="ref15" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Frontinus/De_Aquis/text*.html#note15
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,EdNote,WIDTH,180)"
onMouseOut="nd();">15</A> The distribution of Appia begins at the foot of the Publician Ascent, near the Porta Trigemina, at the place designated as the Salinae.<A CLASS="ref" ID="ref16" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Frontinus/De_Aquis/text*.html#note16
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,EdNote,WIDTH,180)"
onMouseOut="nd();">16</A>

	<P CLASS="justify" ID="p343"><SPAN CLASS="pagenum"> p343 </SPAN>
	<A HREF="
L/Roman/Texts/Frontinus/De_Aquis/text*.html#1.6
	"TARGET="Frontinus"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,LatinOriginal,WIDTH,180)"
onMouseOut="nd();"><IMG TITLE="" WIDTH="30" HEIGHT="20" SRC="
Images/Utility/Flags/medium/Vatican.gif
	" ALT="[Legamen ad versionem Latinam]"></A>
	<A CLASS="chapter" NAME="1.6">6</A>
Forty years after Appia was brought in, in the four hundred and <SPAN CLASS="whole">eighty-first</SPAN> year&#8203;<A CLASS="ref" ID="ref17" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Frontinus/De_Aquis/text*.html#note17
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,EdNote,WIDTH,180)"
onMouseOut="nd();">17</A> from the founding of the City, Manius Curius Dentatus, who held the <SPAN CLASS="whole">censor</SPAN>&shy;ship with Lucius Papirius Cursor, contracted to have the waters of what is now called Old&#8203;<A CLASS="ref" ID="ref18" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Frontinus/De_Aquis/text*.html#note18
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,EdNote,WIDTH,180)"
onMouseOut="nd();">18</A> Anio brought into the City, with the proceeds of the booty captured from Pyrrhus. <A NAME="1.6.2"></A>This was in the second <SPAN CLASS="whole">consul</SPAN>&shy;ship of Spurius Carvilius and Lucius Papirius. <A NAME="1.6.3"></A>Then two years later the question of completing the aqueduct was discussed in the Senate on the motion
	<SPAN CLASS="crux">*
	<IMG TITLE="" WIDTH="49" HEIGHT="12" SRC="
Images/Utility/empty.gif
	" ALT="lacuna"></SPAN>
of the praetor. <A NAME="1.6.4"></A>At the close of the discussion, Curius, who had let the original contract, and Fulvius Flaccus were appointed by decree of the Senate as a board of two to bring in the water. <A NAME="1.6.5"></A>Within five days of the time he had been appointed, one of the two commissioners, Curius, died; thus the credit of achieving the work rested with Flaccus. <A NAME="1.6.6"></A>The intake of Old Anio is above Tibur&#8203;<A CLASS="ref" ID="ref19" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Frontinus/De_Aquis/text*.html#note19
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,EdNote,WIDTH,180)"
onMouseOut="nd();">19</A> at the twentieth milestone outside the
	<SPAN CLASS="crux">*
	<IMG TITLE="" WIDTH="49" HEIGHT="12" SRC="
Images/Utility/empty.gif
	" ALT="lacuna"></SPAN>
Gate, where it gives a part of its water to supply the Tiburtines. <A NAME="1.6.7"></A>Owing to the exigence of elevation,&#8203;<A CLASS="ref" ID="ref20" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Frontinus/De_Aquis/text*.html#note20
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,EdNote,WIDTH,180)"
onMouseOut="nd();">20</A> its conduit has a length of <A CLASS="conversion"
onMouseOver="return Ebox('63.6 km',WIDTH,84)"
onMouseOut="nd();">•</A>43,000 paces. <A NAME="1.6.8"></A>Of this, the channel runs <SPAN CLASS="whole">under</SPAN>&shy;ground for <A CLASS="conversion"
onMouseOver="return Ebox('63,313 meters',WIDTH,156)"
onMouseOut="nd();">•</A>42,779 paces, while there are above ground substructures for <A CLASS="conversion"
onMouseOver="return Ebox('327 m',WIDTH,60)"
onMouseOut="nd();">•</A>221 paces.

	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A HREF="
L/Roman/Texts/Frontinus/De_Aquis/text*.html#1.7
	"TARGET="Frontinus"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,LatinOriginal,WIDTH,180)"
onMouseOut="nd();"><IMG TITLE="" WIDTH="30" HEIGHT="20" SRC="
Images/Utility/Flags/medium/Vatican.gif
	" ALT="[Legamen ad versionem Latinam]"></A>
	<A CLASS="chapter" NAME="1.7">7</A>
One hundred and <SPAN CLASS="whole">twenty-seven</SPAN> years later, that is in the six hundred and eighth year from the founding of the City,&#8203;<A CLASS="ref" ID="ref21" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Frontinus/De_Aquis/text*.html#note21
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,EdNote,WIDTH,180)"
onMouseOut="nd();">21</A> in the <SPAN CLASS="whole">consul</SPAN>&shy;ship of Servius Sulpicius


<A ID="p345"><SPAN CLASS="pagenum"> p345 </SPAN></A>Galba and Lucius Aurelius Cotta, when the conduits of Appia and Old Anio had become leaky by reason of age, and water was also being diverted from them unlawfully by individuals, the Senate commissioned Marcius, who at that time administered the law as praetor between citizens,&#8203;<A CLASS="ref" ID="ref22" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Frontinus/De_Aquis/text*.html#note22
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,EdNote,WIDTH,180)"
onMouseOut="nd();">22</A> to reclaim and repair these conduits; and since the growth of the City was seen to demand a more bountiful supply of water, the same man was charged by the Senate to bring into the City other waters so far as he could.
	<SPAN CLASS="crux">*
	<IMG TITLE="" WIDTH="49" HEIGHT="12" SRC="
Images/Utility/empty.gif
	" ALT="lacuna"></SPAN>
<A NAME="1.7.2"></A>He restored the old channels and brought in a third supply, more wholesome than these,
	<SPAN CLASS="crux">*
	<IMG TITLE="" WIDTH="49" HEIGHT="12" SRC="
Images/Utility/empty.gif
	" ALT="lacuna"></SPAN>
which is called Marcia after the man who introduced it. <A NAME="1.7.3"></A>We read in Fenestella,&#8203;<A CLASS="ref" ID="ref23" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Frontinus/De_Aquis/text*.html#note23
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,EdNote,WIDTH,180)"
onMouseOut="nd();">23</A> that 180,000,000 sesterces&#8203;<A CLASS="ref" ID="ref24" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Frontinus/De_Aquis/text*.html#note24
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,EdNote,WIDTH,180)"
onMouseOut="nd();">24</A> were granted to Marcius for these works, and since the term of his <SPAN CLASS="whole">praetor</SPAN>&shy;ship was not sufficient for the completion of the enterprise, it was extended for a second year. <A NAME="1.7.4"></A>At that time the Decemvirs,&#8203;<A CLASS="ref" ID="ref25" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Frontinus/De_Aquis/text*.html#note25
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,EdNote,WIDTH,180)"
onMouseOut="nd();">25</A> on consulting the Sibylline Books for another purpose, are said to have discovered that it was not right for the Marcian water, or rather the Anio (for tradition more regularly mentions this) to be brought to the Capitol. The matter is said to have been debated in the Senate, in the <SPAN CLASS="whole">consul</SPAN>&shy;ship of Appius Claudius and Quintus Caecilius,&#8203;<A CLASS="ref" ID="ref26" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Frontinus/De_Aquis/text*.html#note26
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,EdNote,WIDTH,180)"
onMouseOut="nd();">26</A> Marcus Lepidus acting as spokesman for the Board of Decemvirs; and three years later the matter is said to have been brought up again by Lucius Lentulus, in the <SPAN CLASS="whole">consul</SPAN>&shy;ship of Gaius Laelius and Quintus


<A ID="p347"><SPAN CLASS="pagenum"> p347 </SPAN></A>Servilius,&#8203;<A CLASS="ref" ID="ref27" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Frontinus/De_Aquis/text*.html#note27
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,EdNote,WIDTH,180)"
onMouseOut="nd();">27</A> but on both occasions the influence of Marcius Rex carried the day; and thus the water was brought to the Capitol. <A NAME="1.7.5"></A>The intake of Marcia is at the <SPAN CLASS="whole">thirty-sixth</SPAN> milestone on the Valerian Way, on a cross-road, three miles to the right as you come from Rome. <A NAME="1.7.6"></A>But on the Sublacensian Way, which was first paved under the Emperor Nero, at the <SPAN CLASS="whole">thirty-eighth</SPAN> milestone, within <A CLASS="conversion"
onMouseOver="return Ebox('296 m',WIDTH,60)"
onMouseOut="nd();">•</A>200 paces to the left [a view of its source may be seen]. Its waters stand like a tranquil pool, of deep green hue. <A NAME="1.7.7"></A>Its conduit has a length, from the intake to the City, of <A CLASS="conversion"
onMouseOver="return Ebox('91,331 m',WIDTH,96)"
onMouseOut="nd();">•</A>61,710½ paces; <A CLASS="conversion"
onMouseOver="return Ebox('80,286 m',WIDTH,96)"
onMouseOut="nd();">•</A>54,247½ paces of <SPAN CLASS="whole">under</SPAN>&shy;ground conduit; <A CLASS="conversion"
onMouseOver="return Ebox('11,045 m',WIDTH,96)"
onMouseOut="nd();">•</A>7,463 paces on structures above ground, of which, at some distance from the City, in several places where it crosses valleys, there are <A CLASS="conversion"
onMouseOver="return Ebox('685 m',WIDTH,60)"
onMouseOut="nd();">•</A>463 paces on arches; nearer the City, beginning at the seventh milestone, <A CLASS="conversion"
onMouseOver="return Ebox('781 m',WIDTH,60)"
onMouseOut="nd();">•</A>528 paces on substructures, and the remaining <A CLASS="conversion"
onMouseOver="return Ebox('9579 m',WIDTH,72)"
onMouseOut="nd();">•</A>6,472 paces on arches.

	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A HREF="
L/Roman/Texts/Frontinus/De_Aquis/text*.html#1.8
	"TARGET="Frontinus"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,LatinOriginal,WIDTH,180)"
onMouseOut="nd();"><IMG TITLE="" WIDTH="30" HEIGHT="20" SRC="
Images/Utility/Flags/medium/Vatican.gif
	" ALT="[Legamen ad versionem Latinam]"></A>
	<A CLASS="chapter" NAME="1.8">8</A>
The Censors, Gnaeus Servilius Caepio and Lucius Cassius Longinus, called Ravilla, in the year 627&#8203;<A CLASS="ref" ID="ref28" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Frontinus/De_Aquis/text*.html#note28
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,EdNote,WIDTH,180)"
onMouseOut="nd();">28</A> after the founding of the City, in the consulate of <SPAN CLASS="emend"><B>Marcus</B></SPAN> Plautus Hypsaeus and Marcus Fulvius Flaccus,&#8203;<A CLASS="ref" ID="ref29" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Frontinus/De_Aquis/text*.html#note29
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,EdNote,WIDTH,180)"
onMouseOut="nd();">29</A> had the water called Tepula brought to Rome and to the Capitol, from the estate of Lucullus, which some persons hold to belong to Tusculan&#8203;<A CLASS="ref" ID="ref30" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Frontinus/De_Aquis/text*.html#note30
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,EdNote,WIDTH,180)"
onMouseOut="nd();">30</A> territory. <A NAME="1.8.2"></A>The intake of Tepula is at the tenth milestone on the Latin Way, near a cross-road, two miles to the right as you proceed from Rome
	<SPAN CLASS="crux">*
	<IMG TITLE="" WIDTH="49" HEIGHT="12" SRC="
Images/Utility/empty.gif
	" ALT="lacuna"></SPAN>
From that point it was conducted in its own&#8203;<A CLASS="ref" ID="ref31" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Frontinus/De_Aquis/text*.html#note31
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,EdNote,WIDTH,180)"
onMouseOut="nd();">31</A> channel to the City.

	<P CLASS="justify" ID="p349"><SPAN CLASS="pagenum"> p349 </SPAN>
	<A HREF="
L/Roman/Texts/Frontinus/De_Aquis/text*.html#1.9
	"TARGET="Frontinus"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,LatinOriginal,WIDTH,180)"
onMouseOut="nd();"><IMG TITLE="" WIDTH="30" HEIGHT="20" SRC="
Images/Utility/Flags/medium/Vatican.gif
	" ALT="[Legamen ad versionem Latinam]"></A>
	<A CLASS="chapter" NAME="1.9">9</A>
Later
	<SPAN CLASS="crux">*
	<IMG TITLE="" WIDTH="49" HEIGHT="12" SRC="
Images/Utility/empty.gif
	" ALT="lacuna"></SPAN>
in the second consulate&#8203;<A CLASS="ref" ID="ref32" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Frontinus/De_Aquis/text*.html#note32
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,EdNote,WIDTH,180)"
onMouseOut="nd();">32</A> of the Emperor Caesar Augustus, when Lucius Volcatius was his colleague, in the year 719&#8203;<A CLASS="ref" ID="ref33" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Frontinus/De_Aquis/text*.html#note33
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,EdNote,WIDTH,180)"
onMouseOut="nd();">33</A> after the foundation of the City, [Marcus] Agrippa, when aedile, after his first <SPAN CLASS="whole">consul</SPAN>&shy;ship,&#8203;<A CLASS="ref" ID="ref34" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Frontinus/De_Aquis/text*.html#note34
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,EdNote,WIDTH,180)"
onMouseOut="nd();">34</A> took another independent source of supply, at the twelfth milestone from the City on the Latin Way, on a cross-road two miles to the right as you proceed from Rome, and also tapped Tepula. <A NAME="1.9.2"></A>The name Julia was given to the new aqueduct by its builder, but since the waters were again divided for distribution, the name Tepula remained.&#8203;<A CLASS="ref" ID="ref35" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Frontinus/De_Aquis/text*.html#note35
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,EdNote,WIDTH,180)"
onMouseOut="nd();">35</A> <A NAME="1.9.3"></A>The conduit of Julia has a length of <A CLASS="conversion"
onMouseOver="return Ebox('22,831 m',WIDTH,96)"
onMouseOut="nd();">•</A>15,426½ paces; <A CLASS="conversion"
onMouseOver="return Ebox('10,360 m',WIDTH,96)"
onMouseOut="nd();">•</A>7,000 paces on masonry above ground, of which <A CLASS="conversion"
onMouseOver="return Ebox('781 m',WIDTH,60)"
onMouseOut="nd();">•</A>528 paces next the City, beginning at the seventh milestone, are on substructures, the other <A CLASS="conversion"
onMouseOver="return Ebox('9,579 m',WIDTH,84)"
onMouseOut="nd();">•</A>6,472 paces being on arches. <A NAME="1.9.4"></A>Past the intake of Julia flows a brook, which is called Crabra. Agrippa refrained from taking in this brook either because he had condemned it, or because he thought it ought to be left to the proprietors at Tusculum, for this is the water which all the estates of that district receive in turn, dealt out to them on regular days and in regular quantities. <A NAME="1.9.5"></A>But our water-men,&#8203;<A CLASS="ref" ID="ref36" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Frontinus/De_Aquis/text*.html#note36
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,EdNote,WIDTH,180)"
onMouseOut="nd();">36</A> failing to practise the same restraint, have always claimed a part of it to supplement Julia, not, however, thus increasing the actual flow of Julia, since they habitually exhausted it by diverting its waters for their own profit. <A NAME="1.9.6"></A>I therefore shut off the Crabra brook and at the Emperor's command restored it entirely to the Tusculan proprietors, who now, possibly not without surprise, take its waters, without knowing to what cause to ascribe the unusual


<A ID="p351"><SPAN CLASS="pagenum"> p351 </SPAN></A>abundance. <A NAME="1.9.7"></A>The Julian aqueduct, on the other hand, by reason of the destruction of the branch pipes through which it was secretly plundered, has maintained its normal quantity even in times of most extraordinary drought. <A NAME="1.9.8"></A>In the same year, Agrippa repaired the conduits of Appia, Old Anio, and Marcia, which had almost worn out, and with unique forethought provided the City with a large number of fountains.

	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A HREF="
L/Roman/Texts/Frontinus/De_Aquis/text*.html#1.10
	"TARGET="Frontinus"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,LatinOriginal,WIDTH,180)"
onMouseOut="nd();"><IMG TITLE="" WIDTH="30" HEIGHT="20" SRC="
Images/Utility/Flags/medium/Vatican.gif
	" ALT="[Legamen ad versionem Latinam]"></A>
	<A CLASS="chapter" NAME="1.10">10</A>
The same man, after his own third <SPAN CLASS="whole">consul</SPAN>&shy;ship, in the <SPAN CLASS="whole">consul</SPAN>&shy;ship of Gaius Sentius and Quintus Lucretius,&#8203;<A CLASS="ref" ID="ref37" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Frontinus/De_Aquis/text*.html#note37
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,EdNote,WIDTH,180)"
onMouseOut="nd();">37</A> twelve years after he had constructed the Julian aqueduct, also brought Virgo to Rome, taking it from the estate of Lucullus. We learn that June 9 was the day that it first began to flow in the City. It was called Virgo,
	<A CLASS="glossary" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/secondary/SMIGRA*/Aquaeductus.html#Virgo.origin_of_name
	"TARGET="princeps"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(EClickHere+'a list of loci for other derivations.<BR><I>(Opens in another window)</I>')"
onMouseOut="nd();">•</A>because a young girl pointed out certain springs to some soldiers hunting for water, and when they followed these up and dug, they found a copious supply. A small temple, situated near the spring, contains a painting which illustrates this origin of the aqueduct. The intake of Virgo is on the Collatian Way at the eighth milestone, in a marshy spot, surrounded by a concrete enclosure for the purpose of confining the gushing waters. Its volume is augmented by several tributaries. Its length is <A CLASS="conversion"
onMouseOver="return Ebox('20,875 m',WIDTH,96)"
onMouseOut="nd();">•</A>14,105 paces. For <A CLASS="conversion"
onMouseOver="return Ebox('19,040 m',WIDTH,96)"
onMouseOut="nd();">•</A>12,865 paces of this distance it is carried in an <SPAN CLASS="whole">under</SPAN>&shy;ground channel, for <A CLASS="conversion"
onMouseOver="return Ebox('1835 m',WIDTH,72)"
onMouseOut="nd();">•</A>1,240 paces above ground. Of these 1,240 paces, it is carried for <A CLASS="conversion"
onMouseOver="return Ebox('799 m',WIDTH,60)"
onMouseOut="nd();">•</A>540 paces on substructures at various points, and for <A CLASS="conversion"
onMouseOver="return Ebox('1036 m',WIDTH,72)"
onMouseOut="nd();">•</A>700 paces on arches. The <SPAN CLASS="whole">under</SPAN>&shy;ground conduits of the tributaries measure <A CLASS="conversion"
onMouseOver="return Ebox('2079 m',WIDTH,72)"
onMouseOut="nd();">•</A>1,405 paces.

	<P CLASS="justify" ID="p353"><SPAN CLASS="pagenum"> p353 </SPAN>
	<A HREF="
L/Roman/Texts/Frontinus/De_Aquis/text*.html#1.11
	"TARGET="Frontinus"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,LatinOriginal,WIDTH,180)"
onMouseOut="nd();"><IMG TITLE="" WIDTH="30" HEIGHT="20" SRC="
Images/Utility/Flags/medium/Vatican.gif
	" ALT="[Legamen ad versionem Latinam]"></A>
	<A CLASS="chapter" NAME="1.11">11</A>
I fail to see what motive induced Augustus, a most sagacious sovereign, to bring in the Alsietinian water, also called Augusta. For this has nothing to commend it, — is in fact positively unwholesome, and for that reason is nowhere delivered for consumption by the people. It may have been that when Augustus began the construction of his Naumachia,&#8203;<A CLASS="ref" ID="ref38" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Frontinus/De_Aquis/text*.html#note38
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,EdNote,WIDTH,180)"
onMouseOut="nd();">38</A> he brought this water in a special conduit, in order not to encroach on the existing supply of wholesome water, and then granted the surplus of the Naumachia to the adjacent gardens and to private users for irrigation. It is customary, however, in the district across the Tiber, in an emergency, whenever the bridges&#8203;<A CLASS="ref" ID="ref39" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Frontinus/De_Aquis/text*.html#note39
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,EdNote,WIDTH,180)"
onMouseOut="nd();">39</A> are undergoing repairs and the water supply is cut off from this side of the river, to draw from Alsietina to maintain the flow of the public fountains. Its source is the Alsietinian Lake, at the fourteenth milestone, on the Claudian Way, on a cross-road, six miles and a half to the right. Its conduit has a length of <A CLASS="conversion"
onMouseOver="return Ebox('32,815 m',WIDTH,96)"
onMouseOut="nd();">•</A>22,172 paces, with <A CLASS="conversion"
onMouseOver="return Ebox('530 m',WIDTH,60)"
onMouseOut="nd();">•</A>358 paces on arches.

	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A HREF="
L/Roman/Texts/Frontinus/De_Aquis/text*.html#1.12
	"TARGET="Frontinus"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,LatinOriginal,WIDTH,180)"
onMouseOut="nd();"><IMG TITLE="" WIDTH="30" HEIGHT="20" SRC="
Images/Utility/Flags/medium/Vatican.gif
	" ALT="[Legamen ad versionem Latinam]"></A>
	<A CLASS="chapter" NAME="1.12">12</A>
To supplement Marcia, whenever dry seasons required an additional supply, Augustus also, by an <SPAN CLASS="whole">under</SPAN>&shy;ground channel, brought to the conduit of Marcia another water of the same excellent quality, called Augusta from the name of its donor. Its source is beyond the springs of Marcia; its conduit, up to its junction with Marcia, measures <A CLASS="conversion"
onMouseOver="return Ebox('1184 m',WIDTH,72)"
onMouseOut="nd();">•</A>800 paces.

	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A HREF="
L/Roman/Texts/Frontinus/De_Aquis/text*.html#1.13
	"TARGET="Frontinus"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,LatinOriginal,WIDTH,180)"
onMouseOut="nd();"><IMG TITLE="" WIDTH="30" HEIGHT="20" SRC="
Images/Utility/Flags/medium/Vatican.gif
	" ALT="[Legamen ad versionem Latinam]"></A>
	<A CLASS="chapter" NAME="1.13">13</A>
After these aqueducts, Gaius Caesar,&#8203;<A CLASS="ref" ID="ref40" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Frontinus/De_Aquis/text*.html#note40
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,EdNote,WIDTH,180)"
onMouseOut="nd();">40</A> the successor of Tiberius, in the second year of his reign, in the


<A ID="p355"><SPAN CLASS="pagenum"> p355 </SPAN></A>consulate of Marcus Aquila Julianus and Publius Nonius Asprenas, in the year 791&#8203;<A CLASS="ref" ID="ref41" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Frontinus/De_Aquis/text*.html#note41
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,EdNote,WIDTH,180)"
onMouseOut="nd();">41</A> after the founding of the City, began two others, inasmuch as the seven then existing seemed insufficient to meet both the public needs and the luxurious private demands of the day. These works Claudius completed on the most magnificent scale,&#8203;<A CLASS="ref" ID="ref42" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Frontinus/De_Aquis/text*.html#note42
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,EdNote,WIDTH,180)"
onMouseOut="nd();">42</A> and dedicated in the <SPAN CLASS="whole">consul</SPAN>&shy;ship of Sulla and Titianus,&#8203;<A CLASS="ref" ID="ref43" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Frontinus/De_Aquis/text*.html#note43
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,EdNote,WIDTH,180)"
onMouseOut="nd();">43</A> on the 1st of August in the year 803&#8203;<A CLASS="ref" ID="ref44" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Frontinus/De_Aquis/text*.html#note44
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,EdNote,WIDTH,180)"
onMouseOut="nd();">44</A> after the founding of the City. To the one water, which had its sources in the Caerulean and <INS CLASS="slip"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(SourceErr+'Curtain</SPAN>')"
onMouseOut="nd();">Curtian</INS> springs, was given the name Claudia. This is next to Marcia in excellence. The second began to be designated as New Anio, in order the more readily to distinguish by title the two Anios that had now begun to flow to the City. To the former Anio the name of "Old" was added.

	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A HREF="
L/Roman/Texts/Frontinus/De_Aquis/text*.html#1.14
	"TARGET="Frontinus"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,LatinOriginal,WIDTH,180)"
onMouseOut="nd();"><IMG TITLE="" WIDTH="30" HEIGHT="20" SRC="
Images/Utility/Flags/medium/Vatican.gif
	" ALT="[Legamen ad versionem Latinam]"></A>
	<A CLASS="chapter" NAME="1.14">14</A>
The intake of Claudia is at the <SPAN CLASS="whole">thirty-eighth</SPAN> milestone on the Sublacensian Way, on a cross-road, <A CLASS="conversion"
onMouseOver="return Ebox('less than 444 meters',WIDTH,225)"
onMouseOut="nd();">•</A>less than three hundred paces to the left. The water comes from two very large and beautiful springs, the Caerulean,&#8203;<A CLASS="ref" ID="ref45" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Frontinus/De_Aquis/text*.html#note45
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,EdNote,WIDTH,180)"
onMouseOut="nd();">45</A> so designated from its appearance, and the Curtian. Claudia also receives the spring which is called Albudinus, which is of such excellence that, when Marcia, too, needs supplementing, this water answers the purpose so admirably that by its addition there is no change in Marcia's quality. The spring of Augusta was turned into Claudia, because it was plainly evident that Marcia was of sufficient volume by itself. But Augusta remained, nevertheless, a reserve supply to Marcia, the understanding being that Augusta should run into Claudia only when the conduit of Marcia would not carry it. Claudia's conduit has a length of <A CLASS="conversion"
onMouseOver="return Ebox('68,977 m',WIDTH,96)"
onMouseOut="nd();">•</A>46,606 paces, of


<A ID="p357"><SPAN CLASS="pagenum"> p357 </SPAN></A>which <A CLASS="conversion"
onMouseOver="return Ebox('53,620 m',WIDTH,96)"
onMouseOut="nd();">•</A>36,230 are in a subterranean channel, <A CLASS="conversion"
onMouseOver="return Ebox('15,060 m',WIDTH,96)"
onMouseOut="nd();">•</A>10,176 on structures above ground; of these last there are at various points in the upper reaches <A CLASS="conversion"
onMouseOver="return Ebox('4522 m',WIDTH,72)"
onMouseOut="nd();">•</A>3,076 paces on arches; and near the City, beginning at the seventh milestone, <A CLASS="conversion"
onMouseOver="return Ebox('901 m',WIDTH,60)"
onMouseOut="nd();">•</A>609 paces on substructures and <A CLASS="conversion"
onMouseOver="return Ebox('9607 m',WIDTH,72)"
onMouseOut="nd();">•</A>6,491 on arches.

	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A HREF="
L/Roman/Texts/Frontinus/De_Aquis/text*.html#1.15
	"TARGET="Frontinus"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,LatinOriginal,WIDTH,180)"
onMouseOut="nd();"><IMG TITLE="" WIDTH="30" HEIGHT="20" SRC="
Images/Utility/Flags/medium/Vatican.gif
	" ALT="[Legamen ad versionem Latinam]"></A>
	<A CLASS="chapter" NAME="1.15">15</A>
The intake of New Anio is at the <SPAN CLASS="whole">forty-second</SPAN> milestone on the Sublacensian Way, in the district of Simbruvium.&#8203;<A CLASS="ref" ID="ref46" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Frontinus/De_Aquis/text*.html#note46
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,EdNote,WIDTH,180)"
onMouseOut="nd();">46</A> The water is taken from the river, which, even without the effect of rainstorms, is muddy and discoloured, because it has rich and cultivated fields adjoining it, and in consequence loose banks. For this reason, a settling reservoir was put in beyond the inlet of the aqueduct, in order that the water might settle there and clarify itself, between the river and the conduit. But even despite this precaution, the water reaches the City in a discoloured condition whenever there are rains. It is joined by the Herculanean brook, which has its source on the same Way, at the <SPAN CLASS="whole">thirty-eighth</SPAN> milestone, opposite the springs of Claudia, beyond the river and the highway. This is naturally very clear, but loses the charm of its purity by admixture with New Anio. The conduit of New Anio measures <A CLASS="conversion"
onMouseOver="return Ebox('86.9 km',WIDTH,84)"
onMouseOut="nd();">•</A>58,700 paces, of which <A CLASS="conversion"
onMouseOver="return Ebox('73.0 km',WIDTH,84)"
onMouseOut="nd();">•</A>49,300 are in an <SPAN CLASS="whole">under</SPAN>&shy;ground channel, <A CLASS="conversion"
onMouseOver="return Ebox('13.9 km',WIDTH,84)"
onMouseOut="nd();">•</A>9,400 paces above ground on masonry; of these, at various points in the upper reaches are <A CLASS="conversion"
onMouseOver="return Ebox('3.4 km',WIDTH,72)"
onMouseOut="nd();">•</A>2,300 paces on substructures or arches; while nearer the City, beginning at the seventh milestone, are <A CLASS="conversion"
onMouseOver="return Ebox('901 meters',WIDTH,120)"
onMouseOut="nd();">•</A>609 paces on substructures, <A CLASS="conversion"
onMouseOver="return Ebox('9607 meters',WIDTH,132)"
onMouseOut="nd();">•</A>6,491 paces on arches. These are the highest arches, rising at certain points to <A CLASS="conversion"
onMouseOver="return Ebox('32.3 meters',WIDTH,132)"
onMouseOut="nd();">•</A>109 feet.

	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A HREF="
L/Roman/Texts/Frontinus/De_Aquis/text*.html#1.16
	"TARGET="Frontinus"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,LatinOriginal,WIDTH,180)"
onMouseOut="nd();"><IMG TITLE="" WIDTH="30" HEIGHT="20" SRC="
Images/Utility/Flags/medium/Vatican.gif
	" ALT="[Legamen ad versionem Latinam]"></A>
	<A CLASS="chapter" NAME="1.16">16</A>
With such an array of indispensable structures carrying so many waters, compare, if you will, the


<A ID="p359"><SPAN CLASS="pagenum"> p359 </SPAN></A>idle Pyramids or the useless, though famous, works of the Greeks!

	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A HREF="
L/Roman/Texts/Frontinus/De_Aquis/text*.html#1.17
	"TARGET="Frontinus"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,LatinOriginal,WIDTH,180)"
onMouseOut="nd();"><IMG TITLE="" WIDTH="30" HEIGHT="20" SRC="
Images/Utility/Flags/medium/Vatican.gif
	" ALT="[Legamen ad versionem Latinam]"></A>
	<A CLASS="chapter" NAME="1.17">17</A>
It has seemed to me not inappropriate to include also a statement of the lengths of the channels of the several aqueducts, according to the kinds of construction.&#8203;<A CLASS="ref" ID="ref47" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Frontinus/De_Aquis/text*.html#note47
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,EdNote,WIDTH,180)"
onMouseOut="nd();">47</A> For since the chief function of this office of water-commissioner lies in their upkeep, the man in charge of them ought to know which of them demand the heavier outlay. My zeal was not satisfied with submitting details to examination; I also had plans made of the aqueducts, on which it is shown where there are valleys and how great these are; where rivers are crossed; and where conduits laid on hillsides demand more particular constant care for their maintenance and repair. By this provision, one reaps the advantage of being able to have the works before one's eyes, so to speak, at a moment's notice, and to consider them as though standing by their side.


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A HREF="
L/Roman/Texts/Frontinus/De_Aquis/text*.html#1.18
	"TARGET="Frontinus"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,LatinOriginal,WIDTH,180)"
onMouseOut="nd();"><IMG TITLE="" WIDTH="30" HEIGHT="20" SRC="
Images/Utility/Flags/medium/Vatican.gif
	" ALT="[Legamen ad versionem Latinam]"></A>
	<A CLASS="chapter" NAME="1.18">18</A>
The several aqueducts reach the City at different elevations. In consequence certain ones deliver water on higher ground, while others cannot rise to the loftier points; for the hills have gradually grown higher with rubbish in consequence of frequent conflagrations. There are five whose head rises to every point in the City, but of these some are forced up with greater, others with lesser pressure. The highest is New Anio; next comes Claudia; the third place is taken by Julia; the fourth by Tepula; the last by Marcia, although at its intake this mounts even to the level of Claudia. But the ancients laid the lines of their aqueducts at a lower elevation, either because they had not yet nicely worked out the art of levelling, or because they purposely sunk


<A ID="p361"><SPAN CLASS="pagenum"> p361 </SPAN></A>their aqueducts in the ground, in order that they might not easily be cut by the enemy, since frequent wars were still waged with the Italians. But now, whenever a conduit has succumbed to old age, it is the practice to carry it in certain parts on substructures or on arches, in order to save length, abandoning the subterranean loops in the valleys.&#8203;<A CLASS="ref" ID="ref48" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Frontinus/De_Aquis/text*.html#note48
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,EdNote,WIDTH,180)"
onMouseOut="nd();">48</A> The sixth rank in height is held by Old Anio, which would likewise be capable of supplying even the higher portions of the City, if it were raised up on substructures or arches, wherever the nature of the valleys and low places demands. Its elevation is followed by that of Virgo, then by that of Appia. These, since they were brought from points near the City, could not rise to such high elevations. Lowest of all is Alsietina, which supplies the ward across the Tiber and the very lowest districts.

	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A HREF="
L/Roman/Texts/Frontinus/De_Aquis/text*.html#1.19
	"TARGET="Frontinus"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,LatinOriginal,WIDTH,180)"
onMouseOut="nd();"><IMG TITLE="" WIDTH="30" HEIGHT="20" SRC="
Images/Utility/Flags/medium/Vatican.gif
	" ALT="[Legamen ad versionem Latinam]"></A>
	<A CLASS="chapter" NAME="1.19">19</A>
Of these waters, six are received in covered catch-basins, this side the seventh milestone on the Latin Way. Here, taking fresh breath, so to speak, after the run, they deposit their sediment. Their volume also is determined by gauges set up at the same point.&#8203;<A CLASS="ref" ID="ref49" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Frontinus/De_Aquis/text*.html#note49
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,EdNote,WIDTH,180)"
onMouseOut="nd();">49</A> Three of these, Julia, Marcia, and Tepula, are carried by the same arches from the catch-basins onward. Tepula, which, as we have above explained,&#8203;<A CLASS="ref" ID="ref50" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Frontinus/De_Aquis/text*.html#note50
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,EdNote,WIDTH,180)"
onMouseOut="nd();">50</A> was tapped and added to the conduit of Julia, now leaves the basin of this same Julia, receives its own quota of water, and runs in its own conduit, under its own name. The topmost of these three is Julia; next below is Tepula; then Marcia.&#8203;<A CLASS="ref" ID="ref51" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Frontinus/De_Aquis/text*.html#note51
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,EdNote,WIDTH,180)"
onMouseOut="nd();">51</A> These flowing [under ground] reach the level of the Viminal Hill, and in fact even of the Viminal Gate. There they again emerge. Yet a part of Julia is


<A ID="p363"><SPAN CLASS="pagenum"> p363 </SPAN></A>first diverted at Spes Vetus, and distributed to the reservoirs of Mount Caelius. But Marcia delivers a part of its waters into the so‑called Herculanean Conduit, behind the Gardens of Pallas.&#8203;<A CLASS="ref" ID="ref52" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Frontinus/De_Aquis/text*.html#note52
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,EdNote,WIDTH,180)"
onMouseOut="nd();">52</A> This conduit, carried along the Caelian, affords no service to the occupants of the hill, on account of its low level; it ends beyond the Porta Capena.

	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A HREF="
L/Roman/Texts/Frontinus/De_Aquis/text*.html#1.20
	"TARGET="Frontinus"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,LatinOriginal,WIDTH,180)"
onMouseOut="nd();"><IMG TITLE="" WIDTH="30" HEIGHT="20" SRC="
Images/Utility/Flags/medium/Vatican.gif
	" ALT="[Legamen ad versionem Latinam]"></A>
	<A CLASS="chapter" NAME="1.20">20</A>
New Anio and Claudia are carried together from their catch-basins on lofty arches, Anio being above.&#8203;<A CLASS="ref" ID="ref53" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Frontinus/De_Aquis/text*.html#note53
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,EdNote,WIDTH,180)"
onMouseOut="nd();">53</A> Their arches end behind the Gardens of Pallas, and from that point their waters are distributed in pipes to serve the City. Yet Claudia first transfers a part of its waters near Spes Vetus to the so‑called Neronian Arches. These arches pass along the Caelian Hill and end near the Temple of the Deified Claudius.&#8203;<A CLASS="ref" ID="ref54" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Frontinus/De_Aquis/text*.html#note54
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,EdNote,WIDTH,180)"
onMouseOut="nd();">54</A> <A NAME="1.20.4"></A>Both aqueducts deliver the volume which they receive, partly about the Caelian, partly on the Palatine and Aventine, and to the ward beyond the Tiber.

	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A HREF="
L/Roman/Texts/Frontinus/De_Aquis/text*.html#1.21
	"TARGET="Frontinus"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,LatinOriginal,WIDTH,180)"
onMouseOut="nd();"><IMG TITLE="" WIDTH="30" HEIGHT="20" SRC="
Images/Utility/Flags/medium/Vatican.gif
	" ALT="[Legamen ad versionem Latinam]"></A>
	<A CLASS="chapter" NAME="1.21">21</A>
Old Anio, this side the fourth milestone, passes under New Anio, which here shifts from the Latin to the Labican Way; it has its own catch-basin. Then, this side the second milestone, it gives a part of its waters to the so‑called Octavian Conduit and reaches the Asinian Gardens&#8203;<A CLASS="ref" ID="ref55" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Frontinus/De_Aquis/text*.html#note55
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,EdNote,WIDTH,180)"
onMouseOut="nd();">55</A> in the neighbourhood of the New Way, whence it is distributed throughout that district. But the main conduit, which passes Spes Vetus, comes inside the
	<A HREF="
E/Gazetteer/Places/Europe/Italy/Lazio/Roma/Rome/_Texts/PLATOP*/Porta_Esquilina.html
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,Platner0,WIDTH,160)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
Esquiline Gate
	</A>
and is distributed to high-lying mains throughout the City.

	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A HREF="
L/Roman/Texts/Frontinus/De_Aquis/text*.html#1.22
	"TARGET="Frontinus"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,LatinOriginal,WIDTH,180)"
onMouseOut="nd();"><IMG TITLE="" WIDTH="30" HEIGHT="20" SRC="
Images/Utility/Flags/medium/Vatican.gif
	" ALT="[Legamen ad versionem Latinam]"></A>
	<A CLASS="chapter" NAME="1.22">22</A>
Neither Virgo, nor Appia, nor Alsietina has a receiving reservoir or catch-basin. The arches of Virgo begin under the
	<A HREF="
E/Gazetteer/Places/Europe/Italy/Lazio/Roma/Rome/_Texts/PLATOP*/Horti_Luculliani.html
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,Platner0,WIDTH,160)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
Lucullan Gardens</A>,&#8203;<A CLASS="ref" ID="ref56" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Frontinus/De_Aquis/text*.html#note56
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,EdNote,WIDTH,180)"
onMouseOut="nd();">56</A> and end on the
	<A HREF="
E/Gazetteer/Places/Europe/Italy/Lazio/Roma/Rome/_Texts/PLATOP*/Campus_Martius.html
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,Platner0,WIDTH,160)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
Campus Martius
	</A>
in front of the
	<A HREF="
E/Gazetteer/Places/Europe/Italy/Lazio/Roma/Rome/_Texts/PLATOP*/Saepta_Julia.html
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,Platner0,WIDTH,160)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
Voting<!-- keep space: --> </A><A ID="p365"><SPAN CLASS="pagenum"> p365 </SPAN></A><A HREF="
E/Gazetteer/Places/Europe/Italy/Lazio/Roma/Rome/_Texts/PLATOP*/Saepta_Julia.html
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,Platner0,WIDTH,160)"
onMouseOut="nd();">Porticoes</A>. The conduit of Appia, running along the base of the Caelian and Aventine, emerges, as we have said above,&#8203;<A CLASS="ref" ID="ref57" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Frontinus/De_Aquis/text*.html#note57
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,EdNote,WIDTH,180)"
onMouseOut="nd();">57</A> at the foot of the Publician Ascent. The conduit of Alsietina terminates behind the Naumachia, for which it seems to have been constructed.

	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A HREF="
L/Roman/Texts/Frontinus/De_Aquis/text*.html#1.23
	"TARGET="Frontinus"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,LatinOriginal,WIDTH,180)"
onMouseOut="nd();"><IMG TITLE="" WIDTH="30" HEIGHT="20" SRC="
Images/Utility/Flags/medium/Vatican.gif
	" ALT="[Legamen ad versionem Latinam]"></A>
	<A CLASS="chapter" NAME="1.23">23</A>
Since I have given in detail the builders of the several aqueducts, their dates, and, in addition, their sources, the lengths of their channels, and their elevations in sequence, it seems to me not out of keeping to add also some separate details, and to show how great is the supply which suffices not only for public and private uses and purposes, but also for the satisfaction of luxury; by how many reservoirs it is distributed and in what wards; how much water is delivered outside the City; how much is used for water-basins, how much for fountains, how much for public buildings, how much in the name of Caesar, how much for private consumption. But before I mention the names <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">quinaria</SPAN>, <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">centenaria</SPAN>, and those of the other ajutages&#8203;<A CLASS="ref" ID="ref58" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Frontinus/De_Aquis/text*.html#note58
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,EdNote,WIDTH,180)"
onMouseOut="nd();">58</A> by which water is gauged, I deem it appropriate to state what is their origin, what their capacities, and what each name means; and, after setting forth the rule according to which their proportions and capacities are computed, to show in what way I discovered their discrepancies, and what course I pursued in correcting them.

	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A HREF="
L/Roman/Texts/Frontinus/De_Aquis/text*.html#1.24
	"TARGET="Frontinus"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,LatinOriginal,WIDTH,180)"
onMouseOut="nd();"><IMG TITLE="" WIDTH="30" HEIGHT="20" SRC="
Images/Utility/Flags/medium/Vatican.gif
	" ALT="[Legamen ad versionem Latinam]"></A>
	<A CLASS="chapter" NAME="1.24">24</A>
The ajutages to measure water are arranged according to the standard either of digits or of inches.&#8203;<A CLASS="ref" ID="ref59" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Frontinus/De_Aquis/text*.html#note59
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,EdNote,WIDTH,180)"
onMouseOut="nd();">59</A> Digits are the standard in Campania and


<A ID="p367"><SPAN CLASS="pagenum"> p367 </SPAN></A>in most parts of Italy; inches are the standard in
	<SPAN CLASS="crux">*
	<IMG TITLE="" WIDTH="49" HEIGHT="12" SRC="
Images/Utility/empty.gif
	" ALT="lacuna"></SPAN>
Now the digit, by common understanding, is <SPAN CLASS="fraction"><SPAN CLASS="top">1</SPAN>&frasl;<SPAN CLASS="bottom">16</SPAN></SPAN> part of a foot;&#8203;<A CLASS="ref" ID="ref60" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Frontinus/De_Aquis/text*.html#note60
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,EdNote,WIDTH,180)"
onMouseOut="nd();">60</A> the inch <SPAN CLASS="fraction"><SPAN CLASS="top">1</SPAN>&frasl;<SPAN CLASS="bottom">12</SPAN></SPAN> part. But precisely as there is a difference between the inch and the digit, just so the standard of the digit itself is not uniform. One is called square; another, round. The square digit is larger than the round digit by <SPAN CLASS="fraction"><SPAN CLASS="top">3</SPAN>&frasl;<SPAN CLASS="bottom">14</SPAN></SPAN> of its own size, while the round is smaller than the square by <SPAN CLASS="fraction"><SPAN CLASS="top">3</SPAN>&frasl;<SPAN CLASS="bottom">11</SPAN></SPAN> of its size, obviously because the corners are cut off.<A CLASS="ref" ID="ref61" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Frontinus/De_Aquis/text*.html#note61
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,EdNote,WIDTH,180)"
onMouseOut="nd();">61</A>

	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A HREF="
L/Roman/Texts/Frontinus/De_Aquis/text*.html#1.25
	"TARGET="Frontinus"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,LatinOriginal,WIDTH,180)"
onMouseOut="nd();"><IMG TITLE="" WIDTH="30" HEIGHT="20" SRC="
Images/Utility/Flags/medium/Vatican.gif
	" ALT="[Legamen ad versionem Latinam]"></A>
	<A CLASS="chapter" NAME="1.25">25</A>
Later on, an ajutage called a <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">quinaria</SPAN>&#8203;<A CLASS="ref" ID="ref62" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Frontinus/De_Aquis/text*.html#note62
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,EdNote,WIDTH,180)"
onMouseOut="nd();">62</A> came into use in the City, to the exclusion of the former measures. This was based neither on the inch, nor on either of the digits, but was introduced, as some think, by Agrippa, or, as others believe, by plumbers at the instance of Vitruvius, the architect. Those who represent Agrippa as its inventor, declare it was so designated because five small ajutages or punctures, so to speak, of the old sort, through which water used to be distributed when the supply was scanty, were now united in one pipe. Those who refer it to Vitruvius and the plumbers, declare that it was so named from the fact that a flat sheet of lead 5 digits wide, made up into a round pipe, forms this ajutage.<A CLASS="comment" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Vitruvius/8*.html#pipe_names
	"TARGET="Vitruvius_E"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(EClickHere+'the passage in Vitruvius: 8.vi.4. (Opens in another window)')"
onMouseOut="nd();">º</A>
But this is indefinite, because the plate, when made up into a round shape, will be extended on the exterior surface and contracted on the interior surface. The most probable explanation is that the <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">quinaria</SPAN>&#8203;<A CLASS="ref" ID="ref63" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Frontinus/De_Aquis/text*.html#note63
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,EdNote,WIDTH,180)"
onMouseOut="nd();">63</A> received its name from having a diameter of <SPAN CLASS="fraction"><SPAN CLASS="top">5</SPAN>&frasl;<SPAN CLASS="bottom">4</SPAN></SPAN> of a digit, a standard which holds in


<A ID="p369"><SPAN CLASS="pagenum"> p369 </SPAN></A>the following ajutages also up to the 20‑pipe, the diameter of each pipe increasing by the addition of ¼ of a digit. For example the 6‑pipe is six quarters in diameter, a 7‑pipe seven quarters, and so on by a uniform increase up to a 20‑pipe.

	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A HREF="
L/Roman/Texts/Frontinus/De_Aquis/text*.html#1.26
	"TARGET="Frontinus"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,LatinOriginal,WIDTH,180)"
onMouseOut="nd();"><IMG TITLE="" WIDTH="30" HEIGHT="20" SRC="
Images/Utility/Flags/medium/Vatican.gif
	" ALT="[Legamen ad versionem Latinam]"></A>
	<A CLASS="chapter" NAME="1.26">26</A>
Every ajutage, now, is gauged either by its diameter or circumference, or by its area of clear cross-section, from any of which factors its capacity becomes evident.&#8203;<A CLASS="ref" ID="ref:Frontinus_and_modern_fluid_dynamics1" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Frontinus/De_Aquis/text*.html#note:Frontinus_and_modern_fluid_dynamics
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,MyNote,WIDTH,150)"
onMouseOut="nd();">a1</A> That we may distinguish the more readily between the inch ajutage, the square digit, the circular digit, and the <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">quinaria</SPAN> itself, use must be made of the value of the <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">quinaria</SPAN>, the ajutage which is most accurately determined and best known. Now the inch ajutage, has a diameter of 1⅓ digits.&#8203;<A CLASS="ref" ID="ref64" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Frontinus/De_Aquis/text*.html#note64
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,EdNote,WIDTH,180)"
onMouseOut="nd();">64</A> Its capacity is [slightly] more than 1⅛ <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">quinariae</SPAN>, <I>i.e.<SPAN CLASS="emend">,</SPAN></I> 1½ twelfths of a <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">quinaria</SPAN> plus <SPAN CLASS="fraction"><SPAN CLASS="top">3</SPAN>&frasl;<SPAN CLASS="bottom">288</SPAN></SPAN> plus ⅔ of <SPAN CLASS="fraction"><SPAN CLASS="top">1</SPAN>&frasl;<SPAN CLASS="bottom">288</SPAN></SPAN> more. The square digit, reduced to the circle is 1 digit plus 1½ twelfths of a digit plus <SPAN CLASS="fraction"><SPAN CLASS="top">1</SPAN>&frasl;<SPAN CLASS="bottom">72</SPAN></SPAN> in diameter; its capacity is <SPAN CLASS="fraction"><SPAN CLASS="top">10</SPAN>&frasl;<SPAN CLASS="bottom">12</SPAN></SPAN> of a <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">quinaria</SPAN>. The circular digit is 1 digit in diameter; its capacity is <SPAN CLASS="fraction"><SPAN CLASS="top">7</SPAN>&frasl;<SPAN CLASS="bottom">12</SPAN></SPAN> plus ½ twelfth plus <SPAN CLASS="fraction"><SPAN CLASS="top">1</SPAN>&frasl;<SPAN CLASS="bottom">72</SPAN></SPAN> of a <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">quinaria</SPAN>.<A CLASS="ref" ID="ref65" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Frontinus/De_Aquis/text*.html#note65
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,EdNote,WIDTH,180)"
onMouseOut="nd();">65</A>

	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A HREF="
L/Roman/Texts/Frontinus/De_Aquis/text*.html#1.27
	"TARGET="Frontinus"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,LatinOriginal,WIDTH,180)"
onMouseOut="nd();"><IMG TITLE="" WIDTH="30" HEIGHT="20" SRC="
Images/Utility/Flags/medium/Vatican.gif
	" ALT="[Legamen ad versionem Latinam]"></A>
	<A CLASS="chapter" NAME="1.27">27</A>
Now the ajutages which are derived from the <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">quinaria</SPAN> increase on two principles. One principle is that the <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">quinaria</SPAN> itself is taken a given number of times, <I>i.e.<SPAN CLASS="emend">,</SPAN></I> in one orifice the equivalent of several <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">quinariae</SPAN> is included, in which case the size of the orifice increases according to the increase in the number of <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">quinariae</SPAN>. This principle is regularly


<A ID="p371"><SPAN CLASS="pagenum"> p371 </SPAN></A>employed, whenever several <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">quinariae</SPAN> are delivered by one pipe and received in a reservoir, from which consumers receive their individual supply, — this being done in order that the conduit may not be tapped too often.<A CLASS="ref" ID="ref66" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Frontinus/De_Aquis/text*.html#note66
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,EdNote,WIDTH,180)"
onMouseOut="nd();">66</A>

	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A HREF="
L/Roman/Texts/Frontinus/De_Aquis/text*.html#1.28
	"TARGET="Frontinus"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,LatinOriginal,WIDTH,180)"
onMouseOut="nd();"><IMG TITLE="" WIDTH="30" HEIGHT="20" SRC="
Images/Utility/Flags/medium/Vatican.gif
	" ALT="[Legamen ad versionem Latinam]"></A>
	<A CLASS="chapter" NAME="1.28">28</A>
The second principle is followed, whenever the pipe does not increase according to some necessary multiple of <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">quinariae</SPAN>, but according to the size of diameters, in conformity with which principle they enlarge their capacity and receive their names; as for example, when a quarter [of a digit] is added to the diameter of a <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">quinaria</SPAN>, we get as a result the <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">senaria</SPAN>,&#8203;<A CLASS="ref" ID="ref67" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Frontinus/De_Aquis/text*.html#note67
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,EdNote,WIDTH,180)"
onMouseOut="nd();">67</A> but its capacity is not increased by a whole <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">quinaria</SPAN>, for it contains a <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">quinaria</SPAN> plus <SPAN CLASS="fraction"><SPAN CLASS="top">5</SPAN>&frasl;<SPAN CLASS="bottom">12</SPAN></SPAN> plus <SPAN CLASS="fraction"><SPAN CLASS="top">1</SPAN>&frasl;<SPAN CLASS="bottom">48</SPAN></SPAN>. So on, by adding successive quarters of a digit to the diameter, as was said above, we get by gradual increases, a 7‑pipe (<SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">septenaria</SPAN>), an 8‑pipe (<SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">octonaria</SPAN>), and up to the 20‑pipe (<SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">vicenaria</SPAN>).

	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A HREF="
L/Roman/Texts/Frontinus/De_Aquis/text*.html#1.29
	"TARGET="Frontinus"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,LatinOriginal,WIDTH,180)"
onMouseOut="nd();"><IMG TITLE="" WIDTH="30" HEIGHT="20" SRC="
Images/Utility/Flags/medium/Vatican.gif
	" ALT="[Legamen ad versionem Latinam]"></A>
	<A CLASS="chapter" NAME="1.29">29</A>
After that&#8203;<A CLASS="ref" ID="ref68" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Frontinus/De_Aquis/text*.html#note68
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,EdNote,WIDTH,180)"
onMouseOut="nd();">68</A> we have the method of gauging which is based on the number of square digits contained in the cross-section, that is, the orifice of each ajutage, from which number of square digits the pipes also get their names. Thus those which in cross-section, that is, in circular orifice, have 25 square digits, are called 25‑pipes. Similarly we have the 30‑pipe (<SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">tricenaria</SPAN>), and so on, by a regular increase of 5 square digits, up to the 120‑pipe.

	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A HREF="
L/Roman/Texts/Frontinus/De_Aquis/text*.html#1.30
	"TARGET="Frontinus"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,LatinOriginal,WIDTH,180)"
onMouseOut="nd();"><IMG TITLE="" WIDTH="30" HEIGHT="20" SRC="
Images/Utility/Flags/medium/Vatican.gif
	" ALT="[Legamen ad versionem Latinam]"></A>
	<A CLASS="chapter" NAME="1.30">30</A>
In the case of the 20‑pipe, which is on the border line between the two methods of gauging,&#8203;<A CLASS="ref" ID="ref69" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Frontinus/De_Aquis/text*.html#note69
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,EdNote,WIDTH,180)"
onMouseOut="nd();">69</A> the two methods almost coincide. For according to the


<A ID="p373"><SPAN CLASS="pagenum"> p373 </SPAN></A>reckoning to be used in the first-named set of ajutages, it is twenty quarter digits in diameter, inasmuch as its diameter is 5 digits; while according to the computation to be applied to the higher ajutages, it has an area of 20 square digits, less a fraction.<A CLASS="ref" ID="ref70" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Frontinus/De_Aquis/text*.html#note70
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,EdNote,WIDTH,180)"
onMouseOut="nd();">70</A>

	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A HREF="
L/Roman/Texts/Frontinus/De_Aquis/text*.html#1.31
	"TARGET="Frontinus"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,LatinOriginal,WIDTH,180)"
onMouseOut="nd();"><IMG TITLE="" WIDTH="30" HEIGHT="20" SRC="
Images/Utility/Flags/medium/Vatican.gif
	" ALT="[Legamen ad versionem Latinam]"></A>
	<A CLASS="chapter" NAME="1.31">31</A>
The gauging of the entire series of ajutages from the 5‑pipe (<SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">quinaria</SPAN>) up to the 120‑pipe, is determined in the way I have explained, and in each class the principle adopted is adhered to for that class. It conforms also to the ajutages set down and verified in the records of our most puissant and patriotic emperor.&#8203;<A CLASS="ref" ID="ref71" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Frontinus/De_Aquis/text*.html#note71
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,EdNote,WIDTH,180)"
onMouseOut="nd();">71</A> Whether, therefore, computation or authority is to be followed, on either ground the ajutages of the records are of greater weight. But the water-men, while they conform to the obvious reckoning in most ajutages, have made deviation in the case of four of them, namely: the 12-, 20-, 100-, and 120‑pipe.

	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A HREF="
L/Roman/Texts/Frontinus/De_Aquis/text*.html#1.32
	"TARGET="Frontinus"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,LatinOriginal,WIDTH,180)"
onMouseOut="nd();"><IMG TITLE="" WIDTH="30" HEIGHT="20" SRC="
Images/Utility/Flags/medium/Vatican.gif
	" ALT="[Legamen ad versionem Latinam]"></A>
	<A CLASS="chapter" NAME="1.32">32</A>
In case of the 12‑pipe, the error is not great, nor is its use frequent. They have added <SPAN CLASS="fraction"><SPAN CLASS="top">1</SPAN>&frasl;<SPAN CLASS="bottom">24</SPAN></SPAN> plus <SPAN CLASS="fraction"><SPAN CLASS="top">1</SPAN>&frasl;<SPAN CLASS="bottom">48</SPAN></SPAN> to its diameter, and to its capacity ¼ of a <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">quinaria</SPAN>. A greater discrepancy is detected in case of the three remaining ajutages. These water-men diminish the 20‑pipe in its diameter by ½ plus <SPAN CLASS="fraction"><SPAN CLASS="top">1</SPAN>&frasl;<SPAN CLASS="bottom">24</SPAN></SPAN> of a digit, its capacity by 3 <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">quinariae</SPAN> plus ¼ plus <SPAN CLASS="fraction"><SPAN CLASS="top">1</SPAN>&frasl;<SPAN CLASS="bottom">24</SPAN></SPAN>; and common use is made of this ajutage for delivery. But in case of the 100‑pipe and 120‑pipe, through which they&#8203;<A CLASS="ref" ID="ref72" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Frontinus/De_Aquis/text*.html#note72
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,EdNote,WIDTH,180)"
onMouseOut="nd();">72</A> regularly receive water, the pipes are not diminished but <I>enlarged!</I> For to the diameter of the 100‑pipe they add ⅔ plus <SPAN CLASS="fraction"><SPAN CLASS="top">1</SPAN>&frasl;<SPAN CLASS="bottom">24</SPAN></SPAN> of a digit, and to the capacity, 10 <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">quinariae</SPAN> plus ½ plus <SPAN CLASS="fraction"><SPAN CLASS="top">1</SPAN>&frasl;<SPAN CLASS="bottom">24</SPAN></SPAN>. To the diameter of the 120‑pipe they add 3 digits plus <SPAN CLASS="fraction"><SPAN CLASS="top">7</SPAN>&frasl;<SPAN CLASS="bottom">12</SPAN></SPAN> plus <SPAN CLASS="fraction"><SPAN CLASS="top">1</SPAN>&frasl;<SPAN CLASS="bottom">24</SPAN></SPAN> plus <SPAN CLASS="fraction"><SPAN CLASS="top">1</SPAN>&frasl;<SPAN CLASS="bottom">48</SPAN></SPAN>; to its capacity, 66 <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">quinariae</SPAN> plus ⅙.

	<P CLASS="justify" ID="p375"><SPAN CLASS="pagenum"> p375 </SPAN>
	<A HREF="
L/Roman/Texts/Frontinus/De_Aquis/text*.html#1.33
	"TARGET="Frontinus"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,LatinOriginal,WIDTH,180)"
onMouseOut="nd();"><IMG TITLE="" WIDTH="30" HEIGHT="20" SRC="
Images/Utility/Flags/medium/Vatican.gif
	" ALT="[Legamen ad versionem Latinam]"></A>
	<A CLASS="chapter" NAME="1.33">33</A>
Thus by diminishing the size of the 20‑pipe by which they constantly deliver, and enlarging the 100- and 120‑pipes, by which they always receive, they steal in case of the 100‑pipe 27 <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">quinariae</SPAN>, and in case of the 120‑pipe 86 <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">quinariae</SPAN>.&#8203;<A CLASS="ref" ID="ref73" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Frontinus/De_Aquis/text*.html#note73
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,EdNote,WIDTH,180)"
onMouseOut="nd();">73</A> While this is proved by computation, it is also obvious from the facts. For from the 20‑pipe, which Caesar rates&#8203;<A CLASS="ref" ID="ref74" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Frontinus/De_Aquis/text*.html#note74
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,EdNote,WIDTH,180)"
onMouseOut="nd();">74</A> at 16 <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">quinariae</SPAN>, they do not deliver more than 13; and it is equally certain that from the 100‑pipe and the 120‑pipe, which they have expanded, they deliver only up to a limited amount, since Caesar, as his records show, has made delivery according to his grant,&#8203;<A CLASS="ref" ID="ref75" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Frontinus/De_Aquis/text*.html#note75
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,EdNote,WIDTH,180)"
onMouseOut="nd();">75</A> when out of each 100‑pipe he furnishes 81½ <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">quinariae</SPAN>, and similarly out of a 120‑pipe, 98.

	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A HREF="
L/Roman/Texts/Frontinus/De_Aquis/text*.html#1.34
	"TARGET="Frontinus"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,LatinOriginal,WIDTH,180)"
onMouseOut="nd();"><IMG TITLE="" WIDTH="30" HEIGHT="20" SRC="
Images/Utility/Flags/medium/Vatican.gif
	" ALT="[Legamen ad versionem Latinam]"></A>
	<A CLASS="chapter" NAME="1.34">34</A>
In all there are 25 ajutages. They all conform to their computed and recorded capacities, barring these four which the water-men have altered. But everything embraced under the head of mensuration ought to be fixed, unchanged, and constant. For only so will any special computation accord with general principles. Just as a <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">sextarius</SPAN>,&#8203;<A CLASS="ref" ID="ref76" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Frontinus/De_Aquis/text*.html#note76
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,EdNote,WIDTH,180)"
onMouseOut="nd();">76</A> for example, has a regular ratio to a <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">cyathus</SPAN>,&#8203;<A CLASS="ref" ID="ref77" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Frontinus/De_Aquis/text*.html#note77
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,EdNote,WIDTH,180)"
onMouseOut="nd();">77</A> and


<A ID="p377"><SPAN CLASS="pagenum"> p377 </SPAN></A>similarly a <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">modius</SPAN>&#8203;<A CLASS="ref" ID="ref78" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Frontinus/De_Aquis/text*.html#note78
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,EdNote,WIDTH,180)"
onMouseOut="nd();">78</A> to both a <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">cyathus</SPAN> and <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">sextarius</SPAN>, so also the multiplication of the <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">quinariae</SPAN> in case of the larger ajutages must follow a regular progression. However, when less is found in the delivery ajutages and more in the receiving ajutages, it is obvious that there is not error, but fraud.

	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A HREF="
L/Roman/Texts/Frontinus/De_Aquis/text*.html#1.35
	"TARGET="Frontinus"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,LatinOriginal,WIDTH,180)"
onMouseOut="nd();"><IMG TITLE="" WIDTH="30" HEIGHT="20" SRC="
Images/Utility/Flags/medium/Vatican.gif
	" ALT="[Legamen ad versionem Latinam]"></A>
	<A CLASS="chapter" NAME="1.35">35</A>
Let us remember that every stream of water, whenever it comes from a higher point and flows into a reservoir after a short run, not only comes up to its measure, but actually yields a surplus; but whenever it comes from a lower point, that is, under less pressure, and is conducted a longer distance, it shrinks in volume, owing to the resistance of its conduit; and that, therefore, on this principle it needs either a check or a help in its discharge.&#8203;<A CLASS="ref" ID="ref79" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Frontinus/De_Aquis/text*.html#note79
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,EdNote,WIDTH,180)"
onMouseOut="nd();">79</A><SPAN CLASS="superscript">•</SPAN>&#8203;<A CLASS="ref" ID="ref:Frontinus_and_modern_fluid_dynamics2" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Frontinus/De_Aquis/text*.html#note:Frontinus_and_modern_fluid_dynamics
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,MyNote,WIDTH,150)"
onMouseOut="nd();">a2</A>

	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A HREF="
L/Roman/Texts/Frontinus/De_Aquis/text*.html#1.36
	"TARGET="Frontinus"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,LatinOriginal,WIDTH,180)"
onMouseOut="nd();"><IMG TITLE="" WIDTH="30" HEIGHT="20" SRC="
Images/Utility/Flags/medium/Vatican.gif
	" ALT="[Legamen ad versionem Latinam]"></A>
	<A CLASS="chapter" NAME="1.36">36</A>
But the position of the <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">calix</SPAN> is also a factor. Placed at right angles and level, it maintains the normal quantity. Set against the current of the water, and sloping downward, it will take in more. If it slopes to one side, so that the water flows by, and if it is inclined with the current, that is, is less favorably placed for taking in water, it will receive the water slowly and in scant quantity. The <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">calix</SPAN>, now, is a bronze ajutage, inserted into a conduit or reservoir, and to it the service pipes are attached. Its length ought not to be less than 12 digits, while its orifice ought to have such capacity as is specified.&#8203;<A CLASS="ref" ID="ref80" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Frontinus/De_Aquis/text*.html#note80
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,EdNote,WIDTH,180)"
onMouseOut="nd();">80</A> Bronze seems to have been selected, since, being hard, it is more difficult to bend, and is not easily expanded or contracted.

	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A HREF="
L/Roman/Texts/Frontinus/De_Aquis/text*.html#1.37
	"TARGET="Frontinus"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,LatinOriginal,WIDTH,180)"
onMouseOut="nd();"><IMG TITLE="" WIDTH="30" HEIGHT="20" SRC="
Images/Utility/Flags/medium/Vatican.gif
	" ALT="[Legamen ad versionem Latinam]"></A>
	<A CLASS="chapter" NAME="1.37">37</A>
I have described below all the 25 ajutages that there are (although only 15 of them are in use), gauging them according to the method of computation


<A ID="p379"><SPAN CLASS="pagenum"> p379 </SPAN></A>spoken of,&#8203;<A CLASS="ref" ID="ref81" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Frontinus/De_Aquis/text*.html#note81
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,EdNote,WIDTH,180)"
onMouseOut="nd();">81</A> and correcting the four which the water-men have altered. To these specifications all ajutages in use ought to conform, or if those four remain in use, they ought to be gauged by the number of <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">quinariae</SPAN> which they contain. The ajutages that are not in use are so referred to.

	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A HREF="
L/Roman/Texts/Frontinus/De_Aquis/text*.html#1.38
	"TARGET="Frontinus"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,LatinOriginal,WIDTH,180)"
onMouseOut="nd();"><IMG TITLE="" WIDTH="30" HEIGHT="20" SRC="
Images/Utility/Flags/medium/Vatican.gif
	" ALT="[Legamen ad versionem Latinam]"></A>
	<A CLASS="chapter" NAME="1.38">38</A>
The inch ajutage&#8203;<A CLASS="ref" ID="ref82" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Frontinus/De_Aquis/text*.html#note82
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,EdNote,WIDTH,180)"
onMouseOut="nd();">82</A> is 1 digit plus ⅓ of a digit in diameter; it contains more than a <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">quinaria</SPAN> by 1½ twelfths of a <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">quinaria</SPAN> plus <SPAN CLASS="fraction"><SPAN CLASS="top">3</SPAN>&frasl;<SPAN CLASS="bottom">288</SPAN></SPAN> plus ⅔ of <SPAN CLASS="fraction"><SPAN CLASS="top">1</SPAN>&frasl;<SPAN CLASS="bottom">288</SPAN></SPAN>. The square digit has the same height as breadth. The square digit converted into its equivalent circle is 1 digit plus 1½ twelfths of a digit plus <SPAN CLASS="fraction"><SPAN CLASS="top">1</SPAN>&frasl;<SPAN CLASS="bottom">72</SPAN></SPAN> in diameter; it measures <SPAN CLASS="fraction"><SPAN CLASS="top">10</SPAN>&frasl;<SPAN CLASS="bottom">12</SPAN></SPAN> of a <I>quinaria</I>. The circular digit is 1 digit in diameter; and measures <SPAN CLASS="fraction"><SPAN CLASS="top">7</SPAN>&frasl;<SPAN CLASS="bottom">12</SPAN></SPAN> plus 1½ twelfth plus <SPAN CLASS="fraction"><SPAN CLASS="top">1</SPAN>&frasl;<SPAN CLASS="bottom">72</SPAN></SPAN> of a <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">quinaria</SPAN> in area.

	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A HREF="
L/Roman/Texts/Frontinus/De_Aquis/text*.html#1.39
	"TARGET="Frontinus"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,LatinOriginal,WIDTH,180)"
onMouseOut="nd();"><IMG TITLE="" WIDTH="30" HEIGHT="20" SRC="
Images/Utility/Flags/medium/Vatican.gif
	" ALT="[Legamen ad versionem Latinam]"></A>
	<A CLASS="chapter" NAME="1.39">39</A>
The <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">quinaria</SPAN>: 1 digit plus <SPAN CLASS="fraction"><SPAN CLASS="top">3</SPAN>&frasl;<SPAN CLASS="bottom">12</SPAN></SPAN> in diameter; 3 digits plus ½ plus <SPAN CLASS="fraction"><SPAN CLASS="top">5</SPAN>&frasl;<SPAN CLASS="bottom">12</SPAN></SPAN> plus <SPAN CLASS="fraction"><SPAN CLASS="top">3</SPAN>&frasl;<SPAN CLASS="bottom">288</SPAN></SPAN> in circumference; it has a capacity of 1 <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">quinaria</SPAN>.

	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A HREF="
L/Roman/Texts/Frontinus/De_Aquis/text*.html#1.40
	"TARGET="Frontinus"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,LatinOriginal,WIDTH,180)"
onMouseOut="nd();"><IMG TITLE="" WIDTH="30" HEIGHT="20" SRC="
Images/Utility/Flags/medium/Vatican.gif
	" ALT="[Legamen ad versionem Latinam]"></A>
	<A CLASS="chapter" NAME="1.40">40</A>
The 6‑pipe: 1½ digits in diameter; 4 digits plus ½ plus <SPAN CLASS="fraction"><SPAN CLASS="top">2</SPAN>&frasl;<SPAN CLASS="bottom">12</SPAN></SPAN> plus <SPAN CLASS="fraction"><SPAN CLASS="top">1</SPAN>&frasl;<SPAN CLASS="bottom">24</SPAN></SPAN> plus <SPAN CLASS="fraction"><SPAN CLASS="top">2</SPAN>&frasl;<SPAN CLASS="bottom">288</SPAN></SPAN> in circumference; it has a capacity of 1 <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">quinaria</SPAN> plus <SPAN CLASS="fraction"><SPAN CLASS="top">5</SPAN>&frasl;<SPAN CLASS="bottom">12</SPAN></SPAN> plus <SPAN CLASS="fraction"><SPAN CLASS="top">7</SPAN>&frasl;<SPAN CLASS="bottom">288</SPAN></SPAN>.

	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A HREF="
L/Roman/Texts/Frontinus/De_Aquis/text*.html#1.41
	"TARGET="Frontinus"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,LatinOriginal,WIDTH,180)"
onMouseOut="nd();"><IMG TITLE="" WIDTH="30" HEIGHT="20" SRC="
Images/Utility/Flags/medium/Vatican.gif
	" ALT="[Legamen ad versionem Latinam]"></A>
	<A CLASS="chapter" NAME="1.41">41</A>
The 7‑pipe: 1 digit plus ½ plus <SPAN CLASS="fraction"><SPAN CLASS="top">3</SPAN>&frasl;<SPAN CLASS="bottom">12</SPAN></SPAN> in diameter; 5 digits plus ½ in circumference; it has a capacity of 1 <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">quinaria</SPAN>, plus ½ plus <SPAN CLASS="fraction"><SPAN CLASS="top">5</SPAN>&frasl;<SPAN CLASS="bottom">12</SPAN></SPAN> plus <SPAN CLASS="fraction"><SPAN CLASS="top">1</SPAN>&frasl;<SPAN CLASS="bottom">24</SPAN></SPAN>; is not in use.

	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A HREF="
L/Roman/Texts/Frontinus/De_Aquis/text*.html#1.42
	"TARGET="Frontinus"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,LatinOriginal,WIDTH,180)"
