<!-- p387 is blank -->
	<H2 ID="p389"><SPAN CLASS="pagenum"> p389 </SPAN>
Book II
	</H2>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A HREF="
L/Roman/Texts/Frontinus/De_Aquis/text*.html#2.64
	"TARGET="Frontinus"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,LatinOriginal,WIDTH,180)"
onMouseOut="nd();"><IMG TITLE="" WIDTH="30" HEIGHT="20" SRC="
Images/Utility/Flags/medium/Vatican.gif
	" ALT="[Legamen ad versionem Latinam]"></A>
	<A CLASS="chapter" NAME="1.64">64</A>
Having detailed those facts which it was necessary to state with reference to the ajutages, I will now set down what discharge each aqueduct, according to the imperial records, was thought to have up to the time of my administration, and also how much it actually did deliver; then the true measure, which I reached by careful investigation, acting on the suggestion of that best and most industrious emperor, Nerva.&#8203;<A CLASS="ref" ID="ref83" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Frontinus/De_Aquis/text*.html#note83
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,EdNote,WIDTH,180)"
onMouseOut="nd();">83</A> Now there were, in the aggregate, 12,755 <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">quinariae</SPAN> set down in the records,&#8203;<A CLASS="ref" ID="ref84" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Frontinus/De_Aquis/text*.html#note84
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,EdNote,WIDTH,180)"
onMouseOut="nd();">84</A> but 14,018 <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">quinariae</SPAN> actually delivered; that is, 1,263 more <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">quinariae</SPAN> were reported as delivered than were reckoned as received.&#8203;<A CLASS="ref" ID="ref85" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Frontinus/De_Aquis/text*.html#note85
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,EdNote,WIDTH,180)"
onMouseOut="nd();">85</A> Since I considered it the most important function of my office to determine the facts concerning the water-supply, my astonishment at this state of affairs stirred me profoundly and led me to investigate how it happened that more was being delivered than belonged to the property, so to speak. Accordingly, I first of all undertook measurements of the intakes of the conduits and discovered a total supply far greater — that is, by about 10,000 <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">quinariae</SPAN> — than I found in the records, as I shall explain in connection with each aqueduct.

	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A HREF="
L/Roman/Texts/Frontinus/De_Aquis/text*.html#2.65
	"TARGET="Frontinus"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,LatinOriginal,WIDTH,180)"
onMouseOut="nd();"><IMG TITLE="" WIDTH="30" HEIGHT="20" SRC="
Images/Utility/Flags/medium/Vatican.gif
	" ALT="[Legamen ad versionem Latinam]"></A>
	<A CLASS="chapter" NAME="2.65">65</A>
In the records Appia is credited with 841 <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">quinariae</SPAN>.<A CLASS="ref" ID="ref86" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Frontinus/De_Aquis/text*.html#note86
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,EdNote,WIDTH,180)"
onMouseOut="nd();">86</A>


<A ID="p391"><SPAN CLASS="pagenum"> p391 </SPAN></A>A gauging of this aqueduct could not be taken at the intake, since there it consists of two channels. But at The Twins, which is below Spes Vetus,&#8203;<A CLASS="ref" ID="ref87" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Frontinus/De_Aquis/text*.html#note87
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,EdNote,WIDTH,180)"
onMouseOut="nd();">87</A> where it joins with a branch of Augusta, I found a depth of water of <A CLASS="conversion"
onMouseOver="return Ebox('1.48 m',WIDTH,72)"
onMouseOut="nd();">•</A>5 feet, and a width of <A CLASS="conversion"
onMouseOver="return Ebox('52 cm',WIDTH,60)"
onMouseOut="nd();">•</A>1¾ feet, making an area of <A CLASS="conversion"
onMouseOver="return Ebox('0.77 m²',WIDTH,50)"
onMouseOut="nd();">•</A>8¾ square feet,&#8203;<A CLASS="ref" ID="ref88" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Frontinus/De_Aquis/text*.html#note88
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,EdNote,WIDTH,180)"
onMouseOut="nd();">88</A> <SPAN CLASS="whole">twenty-two</SPAN> 100‑pipes plus a 40‑pipe, which makes 1,825 <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">quinariae</SPAN>, — more than the records would have it by 984 <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">quinariae</SPAN>. It was delivering 704 <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">quinariae</SPAN>, — 137 <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">quinariae</SPAN> less than credited in the records; and, furthermore, 1,121 <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">quinariae</SPAN> less than given by the gauging at The Twins.&#8203;<A CLASS="ref" ID="ref89" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Frontinus/De_Aquis/text*.html#note89
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,EdNote,WIDTH,180)"
onMouseOut="nd();">89</A> A considerable amount of this, however, is lost by leaks in the conduit, which, being deeply buried, does not clearly exhibit them. And yet their presence is plainly indicated by the fact that in very many parts of the City excellent water is met with, which leaks from that aqueduct. But we also detected some illicit pipes within the City. Outside the City, however, on account of the depth of the level, which at the intake is <A CLASS="conversion"
onMouseOver="return Ebox('14.8 m',WIDTH,72)"
onMouseOut="nd();">•</A>50 feet <SPAN CLASS="whole">under</SPAN>&shy;ground, the conduit suffers no depredations.

	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A HREF="
L/Roman/Texts/Frontinus/De_Aquis/text*.html#2.66
	"TARGET="Frontinus"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,LatinOriginal,WIDTH,180)"
onMouseOut="nd();"><IMG TITLE="" WIDTH="30" HEIGHT="20" SRC="
Images/Utility/Flags/medium/Vatican.gif
	" ALT="[Legamen ad versionem Latinam]"></A>
	<A CLASS="chapter" NAME="2.66">66</A>
Old Anio is credited in the records with the amount of 1,541 <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">quinariae</SPAN>. At the intake I found 4,398 <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">quinariae</SPAN>, exclusive of the quantity which is


<A ID="p393"><SPAN CLASS="pagenum"> p393 </SPAN></A>diverted into the special conduit of the Tiburtines,&#8203;<A CLASS="ref" ID="ref90" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Frontinus/De_Aquis/text*.html#note90
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,EdNote,WIDTH,180)"
onMouseOut="nd();">90</A> — 2,857 <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">quinariae</SPAN> more than is recorded. There were distributed 262 <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">quinariae</SPAN>, before the aqueduct reaches its settling-reservoir. The quantity at the reservoir, determined from the gauges placed there, was 2,362 <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">quinariae</SPAN>, so that 1,774 <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">quinariae</SPAN> were lost between the intake and the reservoir. Down-stream from the settling-reservoir, 1,348 <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">quinariae</SPAN> were delivered, — more than we have stated to be the capacity according to the records by 69 <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">quinariae</SPAN>, but less than we have shown was received into the conduit from the settling-reservoir by 1,014 <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">quinariae</SPAN>. The total which was lost between the intake and the settling-reservoir, amounted to 2,788 <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">quinariae</SPAN>, which I should have suspected resulted from an error of measurement, had I not discovered where it was diverted.<A CLASS="ref" ID="ref91" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Frontinus/De_Aquis/text*.html#note91
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,EdNote,WIDTH,180)"
onMouseOut="nd();">91</A>

	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A HREF="
L/Roman/Texts/Frontinus/De_Aquis/text*.html#2.67
	"TARGET="Frontinus"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,LatinOriginal,WIDTH,180)"
onMouseOut="nd();"><IMG TITLE="" WIDTH="30" HEIGHT="20" SRC="
Images/Utility/Flags/medium/Vatican.gif
	" ALT="[Legamen ad versionem Latinam]"></A>
	<A CLASS="chapter" NAME="2.67">67</A>
In the records Marcia is credited with the quantity of 2,162 <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">quinariae</SPAN>. Gauging it at the intake, I found 4,690 <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">quinariae</SPAN>, — 2,528 <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">quinariae</SPAN> more than appear in the records. There were delivered, before it reaches the settling-reservoir, 95 <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">quinariae</SPAN>; and 92 <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">quinariae</SPAN> were given to supplement Tepula; likewise 164 to Anio. The total delivered before the settling-reservoir is reached, was 351 <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">quinariae</SPAN>. The


<A ID="p395"><SPAN CLASS="pagenum"> p395 </SPAN></A>quantity which is computed at the reservoir from the gauges set up there, along with what is carried around the reservoir and received in the same channel on arches, is 2,944 <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">quinariae</SPAN>. The aggregate of what is delivered above the reservoir or is received on arches is 3,295 <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">quinariae</SPAN>, — more than is set down in the scheduled capacity by 1,133 <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">quinariae</SPAN>, and less than given by the gaugings made at the intake by 1,395 <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">quinariae</SPAN>. After passing the reservoir, it delivered 1,840 <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">quinariae</SPAN>, — 227 <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">quinariae</SPAN> less than we said was set down in the scheduled capacity, and 1,104 <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">quinariae</SPAN> less than is taken from the reservoir upon the arches. The aggregate of what was lost either between the intake and the reservoir or downstream from the reservoir, was 2,499 <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">quinariae</SPAN>, the diversion of which, as in case of the other aqueducts, we discovered at several places. For that there is no lack of water is manifest also from the fact that at the intake, besides the volume which we noted that we found from the capacity of the conduit, over 300 <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">quinariae</SPAN> are wasted.<A CLASS="ref" ID="ref92" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Frontinus/De_Aquis/text*.html#note92
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,EdNote,WIDTH,180)"
onMouseOut="nd();">92</A>

	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A HREF="
L/Roman/Texts/Frontinus/De_Aquis/text*.html#2.68
	"TARGET="Frontinus"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,LatinOriginal,WIDTH,180)"
onMouseOut="nd();"><IMG TITLE="" WIDTH="30" HEIGHT="20" SRC="
Images/Utility/Flags/medium/Vatican.gif
	" ALT="[Legamen ad versionem Latinam]"></A>
	<A CLASS="chapter" NAME="2.68">68</A>
Tepula is credited in the records with 400 <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">quinariae</SPAN>. This aqueduct has no springs; it consists only of some veins of water taken from Julia.&#8203;<A CLASS="ref" ID="ref93" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Frontinus/De_Aquis/text*.html#note93
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,EdNote,WIDTH,180)"
onMouseOut="nd();">93</A> Its intake is therefore to be set down as beginning


<A ID="p397"><SPAN CLASS="pagenum"> p397 </SPAN></A>with the Julian reservoir, for from this it first receives 190 <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">quinariae</SPAN>; then immediately thereafter 92 <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">quinariae</SPAN> from Marcia, and further from New Anio at the Epaphroditian Gardens 163 <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">quinariae</SPAN>. This makes in all 445 <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">quinariae</SPAN>, — more than the records show by 45 <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">quinariae</SPAN>, — which appear in the delivery.<A CLASS="ref" ID="ref94" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Frontinus/De_Aquis/text*.html#note94
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,EdNote,WIDTH,180)"
onMouseOut="nd();">94</A>

	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A HREF="
L/Roman/Texts/Frontinus/De_Aquis/text*.html#2.69
	"TARGET="Frontinus"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,LatinOriginal,WIDTH,180)"
onMouseOut="nd();"><IMG TITLE="" WIDTH="30" HEIGHT="20" SRC="
Images/Utility/Flags/medium/Vatican.gif
	" ALT="[Legamen ad versionem Latinam]"></A>
	<A CLASS="chapter" NAME="2.69">69</A>
Julia is credited in the records with a measure of 649 <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">quinariae</SPAN>. At the intake the gaugings could not be made, because the intake is composed of several tributaries. But at the sixth mile-stone from the City, Julia is wholly taken into the settling reservoir, at which place its volume, according to the plainly visible gauges, amounts to 1,206 <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">quinariae</SPAN>, — more than set down in the records by 557 <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">quinariae</SPAN>. Besides this, near the City, behind the Gardens of Pallas, it receives from Claudia 162 <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">quinariae</SPAN>, making the whole number of <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">quinariae</SPAN> received by Julia 1,368. Of this amount, it discharges 190 into Tepula, and delivers on its own account 803 <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">quinariae</SPAN>; from this we get a total of 993 <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">quinariae</SPAN> which it delivers, — more than the records credit by 344 <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">quinariae</SPAN>; less than we set it down as having at the reservoir by 213, which is precisely the amount we found diverted by those who were taking water without a grant from the sovereign.<A CLASS="ref" ID="ref95" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Frontinus/De_Aquis/text*.html#note95
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,EdNote,WIDTH,180)"
onMouseOut="nd();">95</A>

	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A HREF="
L/Roman/Texts/Frontinus/De_Aquis/text*.html#2.70
	"TARGET="Frontinus"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,LatinOriginal,WIDTH,180)"
onMouseOut="nd();"><IMG TITLE="" WIDTH="30" HEIGHT="20" SRC="
Images/Utility/Flags/medium/Vatican.gif
	" ALT="[Legamen ad versionem Latinam]"></A>
	<A CLASS="chapter" NAME="2.70">70</A>
Virgo is credited in the records with a measure of 652 <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">quinariae</SPAN>. I could not take a gauging of this


<A ID="p399"><SPAN CLASS="pagenum"> p399 </SPAN></A>at the intake, because Virgo is made up of several tributaries, and enters its channels with too slow a current. Near the City, however, at the seventh mile-stone, on the land which now belongs to Cejonius Commodus, where Virgo has a greater velocity, I made a gauging, and it amounted to 2,504 <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">quinariae</SPAN>, — 1,852 <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">quinariae</SPAN> more than was set down in the records. The correctness of our gauging is very easily proved; for Virgo discharges all the <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">quinariae</SPAN> which we found by gauging, that is, 2,504.

	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A HREF="
L/Roman/Texts/Frontinus/De_Aquis/text*.html#2.71
	"TARGET="Frontinus"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,LatinOriginal,WIDTH,180)"
onMouseOut="nd();"><IMG TITLE="" WIDTH="30" HEIGHT="20" SRC="
Images/Utility/Flags/medium/Vatican.gif
	" ALT="[Legamen ad versionem Latinam]"></A>
	<A CLASS="chapter" NAME="2.71">71</A>
The measure of the capacity of Alsietina is not set down in the records, nor could it be accurately arrived at under present conditions, because [it receives] from Lake Alsietinus, and afterwards in the vicinity of Careiae from Sabatinus as much water as the water-men arrange for. Alsietina delivers 392 <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">quinariae</SPAN>.

	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A HREF="
L/Roman/Texts/Frontinus/De_Aquis/text*.html#2.72
	"TARGET="Frontinus"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,LatinOriginal,WIDTH,180)"
onMouseOut="nd();"><IMG TITLE="" WIDTH="30" HEIGHT="20" SRC="
Images/Utility/Flags/medium/Vatican.gif
	" ALT="[Legamen ad versionem Latinam]"></A>
	<A CLASS="chapter" NAME="2.72">72</A>
Claudia, flowing more abundantly than the others, is especially exposed to depredation. In the records it is credited with only 2,855 <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">quinariae</SPAN>, although I found at the intake 4,607 <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">quinariae</SPAN>, — 1,752 <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">quinariae</SPAN> more than are recorded. Our gauging, however, is confirmed by the fact that at the seventh mile-stone from the City, at the settling reservoir, where the gauging is without question, we find 3,312 <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">quinariae</SPAN>, — 457 more than are recorded, although, before reaching the reservoir, not only are deliveries made, to satisfy private grants, but also, as we detected, a great deal is taken secretly, and therefore 1,295 <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">quinariae</SPAN> less are found than there really ought to be. Moreover, in the delivery of the water also it is manifest that there is fraud, since the amount actually delivered does not agree either with the statements of the records or with the gaugings


<A ID="p401"><SPAN CLASS="pagenum"> p401 </SPAN></A>made by us at the intake, or even with those made at the settling-basins, after so many depredations. For there are only 1,750 <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">quinariae</SPAN> delivered, — less than the computation given in the records by 1,105 <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">quinariae</SPAN>; also less than is shown by the gauging made at the intake by 2,857 <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">quinariae</SPAN>, and less also than is found at the reservoir by 1,562 <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">quinariae</SPAN>.&#8203;<A CLASS="ref" ID="ref96" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Frontinus/De_Aquis/text*.html#note96
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,EdNote,WIDTH,180)"
onMouseOut="nd();">96</A> For this reason, although it arrived in the City perfectly clear in its own conduit, it was mixed within the City with the New Anio, so that by creating confusion, the quantity as well as the distribution of the two might be obscured. But should any one think that I exaggerate the measure of the water received, such a person must be reminded that the Caerulean and Curtian sources&#8203;<A CLASS="ref" ID="ref97" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Frontinus/De_Aquis/text*.html#note97
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,EdNote,WIDTH,180)"
onMouseOut="nd();">97</A> of the Claudian aqueduct are so ample for supplying to their conduit the 4,607 <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">quinariae</SPAN> which I have indicated, that 1,600 besides go to waste.&#8203;<A CLASS="ref" ID="ref98" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Frontinus/De_Aquis/text*.html#note98
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,EdNote,WIDTH,180)"
onMouseOut="nd();">98</A> But at the same time I do not deny that this superabundance does not really belong to these springs, for it comes from Augusta. This was devised to supplement Marcia, but is turned into the sources of Claudia, when Marcia does not need it, though not even the conduit of Claudia itself can carry all this water.<A CLASS="ref" ID="ref99" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Frontinus/De_Aquis/text*.html#note99
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,EdNote,WIDTH,180)"
onMouseOut="nd();">99</A>

	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A HREF="
L/Roman/Texts/Frontinus/De_Aquis/text*.html#2.73
	"TARGET="Frontinus"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,LatinOriginal,WIDTH,180)"
onMouseOut="nd();"><IMG TITLE="" WIDTH="30" HEIGHT="20" SRC="
Images/Utility/Flags/medium/Vatican.gif
	" ALT="[Legamen ad versionem Latinam]"></A>
	<A CLASS="chapter" NAME="2.73">73</A>
New Anio was put down in the records as having 3,263 <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">quinariae</SPAN>. Gauging at the intake I found 4,738 <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">quinariae</SPAN>, — more than the scheduled capacity by 1,475 <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">quinariae</SPAN>. In what other way could I more clearly show that I do not exaggerate the number of <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">quinariae</SPAN> at the intake than by the fact that in


<A ID="p403"><SPAN CLASS="pagenum"> p403 </SPAN></A>the records of delivery most of this water is actually accounted for? For it is stated that 4,200 <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">quinariae</SPAN> are delivered,&#8203;<A CLASS="ref" ID="ref100" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Frontinus/De_Aquis/text*.html#note100
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,EdNote,WIDTH,180)"
onMouseOut="nd();">100</A> although elsewhere in the same records the amount taken in is put down as only 3,263. Besides this, I have discovered that not only 538 <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">quinariae</SPAN> (the difference between our gauging and the recorded delivery) are stolen, but a far greater quantity. Whence it appears that the total found by me is none too large.&#8203;<A CLASS="ref" ID="ref101" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Frontinus/De_Aquis/text*.html#note101
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,EdNote,WIDTH,180)"
onMouseOut="nd();">101</A> The explanation of this is, that the swifter current of water, coming as it does from a large and rapidly flowing river, increases the volume by its very velocity.&#8203;<A CLASS="ref" ID="ref102" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Frontinus/De_Aquis/text*.html#note102
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,EdNote,WIDTH,180)"
onMouseOut="nd();">102</A><SPAN CLASS="superscript">•</SPAN>&#8203;<A CLASS="ref" ID="ref:Frontinus_and_modern_fluid_dynamics3" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Frontinus/De_Aquis/text*.html#note:Frontinus_and_modern_fluid_dynamics
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,MyNote,WIDTH,150)"
onMouseOut="nd();">a3</A>

	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A HREF="
L/Roman/Texts/Frontinus/De_Aquis/text*.html#2.74
	"TARGET="Frontinus"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,LatinOriginal,WIDTH,180)"
onMouseOut="nd();"><IMG TITLE="" WIDTH="30" HEIGHT="20" SRC="
Images/Utility/Flags/medium/Vatican.gif
	" ALT="[Legamen ad versionem Latinam]"></A>
	<A CLASS="chapter" NAME="2.74">74</A>
I do not doubt that many will be surprised that according to our gaugings, the quantity of water was found to be much greater than that given in the imperial records.&#8203;<A CLASS="ref" ID="ref103" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Frontinus/De_Aquis/text*.html#note103
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,EdNote,WIDTH,180)"
onMouseOut="nd();">103</A> The reason for this is to be found


<A ID="p405"><SPAN CLASS="pagenum"> p405 </SPAN></A>in the blunders of those who carelessly computed each of these waters at the outset. Moreover, I am prevented from believing that it was from fear of droughts in the summer that they deviated so far from the truth, for the reason that I myself made my gaugings in the month of July, and found the above-recorded supply of each one remaining constant throughout the entire remainder of the summer. But whatever the reason may be, it has any rate been discovered that 10,000 <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">quinariae</SPAN> were intercepted, while the amounts granted by the sovereign are limited to the quantities set down in the records.

	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A HREF="
L/Roman/Texts/Frontinus/De_Aquis/text*.html#2.75
	"TARGET="Frontinus"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,LatinOriginal,WIDTH,180)"
onMouseOut="nd();"><IMG TITLE="" WIDTH="30" HEIGHT="20" SRC="
Images/Utility/Flags/medium/Vatican.gif
	" ALT="[Legamen ad versionem Latinam]"></A>
	<A CLASS="chapter" NAME="2.75">75</A>
Another variance consists in this, that one measure is used at the intake, another, considerably smaller, at the settling-reservoir, and the smallest at the point of distribution. The cause of this is the dishonesty of the water-men, whom we have detected diverting water from the public conduits for private use. But a large number of landed proprietors also, past whose fields the aqueducts run, tap the conduits; whence it comes that the public water-courses are actually brought to a standstill by private citizens, just to water their gardens.

	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A HREF="
L/Roman/Texts/Frontinus/De_Aquis/text*.html#2.76
	"TARGET="Frontinus"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,LatinOriginal,WIDTH,180)"
onMouseOut="nd();"><IMG TITLE="" WIDTH="30" HEIGHT="20" SRC="
Images/Utility/Flags/medium/Vatican.gif
	" ALT="[Legamen ad versionem Latinam]"></A>
	<A CLASS="chapter" NAME="2.76">76</A>
Concerning misdemeanours of this sort, nothing more nor better needs to be said than was said by Caelius Rufus,&#8203;<A CLASS="ref" ID="ref104" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Frontinus/De_Aquis/text*.html#note104
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,EdNote,WIDTH,180)"
onMouseOut="nd();">104</A> in his speech, which is entitled "Concerning Waters." And would that we were not having daily experience by actual infringement of the law that all these misdemeanours are committed just as flagrantly now as then. We have found irrigated fields, shops, garrets even, and lastly all disorderly houses fitted up with fixtures through which a constant supply of flowing water might be assured. For that some waters should be delivered under a


<A ID="p407"><SPAN CLASS="pagenum"> p407 </SPAN></A>forged name in place of other waters belongs to the lesser misdemeanours. But among the frauds that seemed to demand correction, is to be mentioned what took place in the vicinity of the Caelian and Aventine Hills. These hills, before the construction of Claudia, utilized the waters of Marcia and Julia; but after the Emperor Nero led Claudia over the arches at Spes Vetus up to the Temple of the Deified Claudius,&#8203;<A CLASS="ref" ID="ref105" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Frontinus/De_Aquis/text*.html#note105
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,EdNote,WIDTH,180)"
onMouseOut="nd();">105</A> in order to distribute it from there, the first named waters, instead of being augmented by this new supply, were themselves allowed to go unused;&#8203;<A CLASS="ref" ID="ref106" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Frontinus/De_Aquis/text*.html#note106
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,EdNote,WIDTH,180)"
onMouseOut="nd();">106</A> for he did not build new reservoirs for Claudia, but used those that already existed; and the old name of these remained, although the water had become a new one.

	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A HREF="
L/Roman/Texts/Frontinus/De_Aquis/text*.html#2.77
	"TARGET="Frontinus"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,LatinOriginal,WIDTH,180)"
onMouseOut="nd();"><IMG TITLE="" WIDTH="30" HEIGHT="20" SRC="
Images/Utility/Flags/medium/Vatican.gif
	" ALT="[Legamen ad versionem Latinam]"></A>
	<A CLASS="chapter" NAME="2.77">77</A>
With this, enough has been said about the volume of each aqueduct, and, if I may so express it, about a new way of acquiring water;&#8203;<A CLASS="ref" ID="ref107" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Frontinus/De_Aquis/text*.html#note107
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,EdNote,WIDTH,180)"
onMouseOut="nd();">107</A> about frauds and about offences committed in connection with all this. It remains to account in detail for the supply delivered (which we found given collectively and in a lump sum, so to speak, — and even set down under false entries),&#8203;<A CLASS="ref" ID="ref108" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Frontinus/De_Aquis/text*.html#note108
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,EdNote,WIDTH,180)"
onMouseOut="nd();">108</A> and to do this according to the several aqueducts and to the several wards of the City. I know very well that such an enumeration will appear not only dry but also complicated; nevertheless, I will make it — but as short as possible — that nothing may be lacking to the data of this office. Those who are satisfied with knowing the totals, may skip the details.

	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A HREF="
L/Roman/Texts/Frontinus/De_Aquis/text*.html#2.78
	"TARGET="Frontinus"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,LatinOriginal,WIDTH,180)"
onMouseOut="nd();"><IMG TITLE="" WIDTH="30" HEIGHT="20" SRC="
Images/Utility/Flags/medium/Vatican.gif
	" ALT="[Legamen ad versionem Latinam]"></A>
	<A CLASS="chapter" NAME="2.78">78</A>
Now the distribution of the 14,018 <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">quinariae</SPAN> is so recorded that the 771 <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">quinariae</SPAN>&#8203;<A CLASS="ref" ID="ref109" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Frontinus/De_Aquis/text*.html#note109
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,EdNote,WIDTH,180)"
onMouseOut="nd();">109</A> which are transferred


<A ID="p409"><SPAN CLASS="pagenum"> p409 </SPAN></A>from certain aqueducts to supplement others and are set down twice in showing the distribution, figure only once in reckoning. Of this quantity there are delivered outside the City, 4,063 <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">quinariae</SPAN>, 1,718 <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">quinariae</SPAN> in the name of Caesar,&#8203;<A CLASS="ref" ID="ref110" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Frontinus/De_Aquis/text*.html#note110
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,EdNote,WIDTH,180)"
onMouseOut="nd();">110</A> to private parties, 2,345. The remaining 9,955 were distributed within the City to 247 reservoirs; of these there were delivered in the name of Caesar 1,707½ <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">quinariae</SPAN>, to private parties 3,847 <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">quinariae</SPAN>, for public uses 4,401 <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">quinariae</SPAN>, — namely to
	<SPAN CLASS="colorFFDD99">*</SPAN>
	<IMG TITLE="" WIDTH="77" HEIGHT="12" SRC="
Images/Utility/empty.gif
	" ALT="lacuna">&#8203;<A CLASS="ref" ID="ref111" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Frontinus/De_Aquis/text*.html#note111
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,EdNote,WIDTH,180)"
onMouseOut="nd();">111</A>
camps 279 <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">quinariae</SPAN>, to <SPAN CLASS="whole">seventy-five</SPAN> public structures 2,301 <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">quinariae</SPAN>, to <SPAN CLASS="whole">thirty-nine</SPAN> ornamental fountains 386 <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">quinariae</SPAN>, to five hundred and <SPAN CLASS="whole">ninety-one</SPAN> water-basins 1,335 <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">quinariae</SPAN>. But the schedule must be made to apply also to the several aqueducts and to the several wards of the City.<A CLASS="ref" ID="ref112" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Frontinus/De_Aquis/text*.html#note112
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,EdNote,WIDTH,180)"
onMouseOut="nd();">112</A>

	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A HREF="
L/Roman/Texts/Frontinus/De_Aquis/text*.html#2.79
	"TARGET="Frontinus"
