On the Pincian.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note57" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Frontinus/De_Aquis/text*.html#ref57
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">57</A>
<I>Cf.</I> <A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Frontinus/De_Aquis/text*.html#1.5
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,5,WIDTH,140)"
onMouseOut="nd();">5</A>.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note58" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Frontinus/De_Aquis/text*.html#ref58
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">58</A>
The ajutage was the nozzle, fitted to the water-pipe. The size and character of the ajutage, therefore, were important factors in the measurement of the water discharged. The ajutage was gauged according to various principles. <I>Cf.</I> <A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Frontinus/De_Aquis/text*.html#1.26
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,5,WIDTH,140)"
onMouseOut="nd();">26</A>.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note59" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Frontinus/De_Aquis/text*.html#ref59
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">59</A>
One of the most serious abuses practised by the water-men at Rome was connected with the size of the pipes used in the receiving and the distribution of water. <I>Cf.</I> <A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Frontinus/De_Aquis/text*.html#2.112
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,5,WIDTH,140)"
onMouseOut="nd();">112, 113, 114</A>. Since the size and position (<I>cf.</I> <A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Frontinus/De_Aquis/text*.html#1.36
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,5,WIDTH,140)"
onMouseOut="nd();">36</A>) of the ajutage controlled the amount discharged, it was necessary to know 


<A ID="p365x"></A>the exact capacity of each type, and Frontinus, therefore, enumerates these first of all.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note60" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Frontinus/De_Aquis/text*.html#ref60
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">60</A>
The Roman foot measured 11.6 English inches, 0.296 m.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note61" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Frontinus/De_Aquis/text*.html#ref61
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">61</A>
The difference between the areas of a square digit and a round digit whose diameter is equal to the side of the square digit is easily seen: <IMG TITLE="" WIDTH="18" HEIGHT="18" SRC="
Images/Roman/Texts/Frontinus/De_Aquis/circle_inscribed_in_a_square*.jpg
			" ALT="[A circle inscribed in a square]">


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note62" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Frontinus/De_Aquis/text*.html#ref62
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">62</A>
The <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">quinaria</SPAN> was a measure not of volume but of capacity, <I>i.e.</I> as much water as would flow through a pipe one and a quarter digits in diameter, constantly discharging under pressure. "A <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">quinaria</SPAN> was about 5,000 or 6,000 


<A ID="p367x"></A>United States gallons per <SPAN CLASS="whole">twenty-four</SPAN> hours, plus or minus 2,000 or 3,000 gallons, according to circumstances, favourable or unfavourable" (Herschel).


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note63" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Frontinus/De_Aquis/text*.html#ref63
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">63</A>
<I>i.e.</I> "a fiver."


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note64" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Frontinus/De_Aquis/text*.html#ref64
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">64</A>
<I>Cf.</I> <A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Frontinus/De_Aquis/text*.html#1.38
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,5,WIDTH,140)"
onMouseOut="nd();">38 ff.
	</A>


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note65" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Frontinus/De_Aquis/text*.html#ref65
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">65</A>
Frontinus's fractions and the symbols which represent them are as follows. The total value in each case is the <I>sum</I> of the various members.

